More than 90% of the airline's staff are based in Australia.

$1m payoff for former Shell boss Judy Boynton. Shell told shocked investors that its reserves were 20% smaller than previously thought. In September, it paid £82.7m in fines to regulators on both sides of the Atlantic for violating market rules in its reporting of reserves.

US firm 'bids for Lacroix label' LVMH has been selling non-core businesses and focusing on its most profitable labels. Privately-held Falic Group bought two cosmetics brands, Hard Candy and Urban Decay, in early 2003. The Florida company also own a chain of 90 duty free stores in the US.

Nigerian banks United Bank of Africa and Standard Trust Bank agree to merge. The merger will create the biggest bank in West Africa. No financial details were revealed. Deal is in line with a 2004 directive from the Nigerian central bank that called for more consolidation in the nation's banking sector.

Borrowing costs are tipped to rise by a quarter of a percentage point to 2.25%. The move comes as a recovery in the US economy shows signs of robustness and sustainability. The dollar's record-breaking decline, meanwhile, has spooked markets and raised concerns about the pace of inflation.

Parmalat was placed into bankruptcy protection in 2003 after a 14bn euro black hole was found in its accounts. More than 130,000 people lost money following the firm's collapse. Mr Tanzi issued a statement through his lawyer after five hours of questioning by prosecutors in Parma.

Dollar slides ahead of New Year. Analysts predict that more declines are likely in 2005. Japanese yen touched its lowest versus the euro on concerns about economic growth in Asia. Investors are concerned about the size of the US trade and budget deficits and are betting that George W Bush's administration will allow the dollar to weaken.

Citizens Bank and Canal Bank used 13,000 slaves as collateral between 1831 and 1865. The two lenders are now closed, but were linked to Bank One, which JP Morgan bought last year. "The slavery era was a tragic time in US history and in our company's history," the bank said.

EU-US seeking deal on air dispute. Airbus and Boeing accuse each other of benefiting from illegal subsidies. US terminated an agreement with the EU, reached in 1992, which limits the subsidies countries can hand over to civil aircraft makers. UPS has placed an order for 10 Airbus A380 superjumbo freight-carrying jets.

Brazil approves bankruptcy reform. New regulations will limit payments to workers to 150 times the minimum monthly salary, which is currently $94. Law also makes it more difficult for a company to declare bankruptcy. When a firm is declared bankrupt it will gain protection from creditors for 180 days while a recovery plan is worked out.

China has 350 million smokers who consumer 1.7 trillion cigarettes a year. Smoking is fashionable in China, where it is seen as an essential - and manly - sociable touch. Ban threatens to reignite tensions between the regulator and British American Tobacco, which plans to become China's first foreign cigarette maker.

GW Pharma's Sativex mouth spray could be legally available to MS sufferers in Canada within the next few months. This will be the first time a cannabis-based drug has been approved anywhere in the world, representing a landmark for GW Pharma and for patients with MS.

Yukos is due in a US court on Thursday as it continues to fight for its survival. Firm is in the process of being broken up by Russian authorities in order to pay a $27bn (£14bn) tax bill. Yukos wants damages of $20bn, claiming Yuganskneftegas was sold at less than market value.

Council of Mortgage Lenders (CML), British Bankers Association (BBA) and Building Societies Association all say mortgage lending is slowing. CML figures showed gross lending fell by 4% in November as the number of people buying new homes fell. Rightmove says owners must indulge in a "winter sale" and slash prices by up to 8%.

Mystery surrounds new Yukos owner Baikal Finance Group. Gazprom had been expected to win the auction but is thought to have failed to get finance for the deal after a US court injunction barred it from taking part. The sale has bought time for Gaz Prom to raise the money needed to purchase the firm.

The deal will help the carrier, trying to survive by cutting costs by nearly $1bn (£530m) a year, save about $94m. More than two thirds of its 28,000 staff have now accepted wage cuts. The seventh largest carrier in the US sought bankruptcy protection for a second time in two years last September.

Argentina has made a remarkable recovery from a hideous and lengthy recession. The country's economy is set to grow about 8% this year after seeing 9% growth last year. Argentina is still burdened by its failure to pay private creditors at the end of 2001.

VW considers opening Indian plant but has yet to make a final decision. VW's proposed plant would be set up in the port city of Visakhapatnam on India's eastern coast. Several foreign carmakers, including Hyundai, Toyota, Suzuki and Ford, already have Indian production facilities.

Gross domestic product rose by 1.7% last year, the statistical office said. Foreign sales increased by 8.2% compared with a 0.3% slide in private consumption. Concerns remain over the strength of the euro, weak domestic demand and a sluggish labour market.

Tsunami to cost Sri Lanka $1.3bn (£691m) in 2005 for reconstruction. Island state is asking for about $320m from the International Monetary Fund. Some 150,000 people across the region are feared to be dead and millions have been left homeless and destitute.

Stephanie Villalba, 42, won her claim of unfair dismissal, resulting from her sacking in August 2003. Her partial victory is likely to cap her compensation to about £55,000, a tiny fraction of what she asked for. The extent of damages will be assessed in the New Year. Merrill said she was removed because of extensive losses the firm was suffering on the continent.

Axa Sun Life has lowered annual bonus payouts for up to 50,000 with-profits investors. The cut will hit an estimated 3% of Axa's policyholders. Heavy stock market falls throughout 2001 and 2002 forced most firms to trim bonus rates on their policies.

GM's revenues rose 4.7% to $51.2bn from $48.8bn a year earlier. European losses at General Motors Europe totalled $345m in the fourth quarter of 2004. GM said its profits were also hit by higher healthcare costs in US.

Strong quarterly growth for Nike. Revenues increased 11% to $3.1bn, from $2.8bn for the same period in 2003. Nike, whose products are endorsed by Tiger Woods among other sports stars, said "demand continues to grow"

Firms led by the Oil & Natural Gas Corporation (ONGC) will also assist in the development of Iranian oil fields. Ministers, eager to gain access to energy supplies to meet the demands of a booming economy, secured a similar deal to one between Iran and China. ONGC said it was in talks to buy former assets of troubled Russian oil firm Yukos.

China accounted for 20.1% of Japan's trade in 2004, compared with 18.6% for the US. The change highlights China's growing importance as an economic powerhouse. In 2003, the U.S. was ahead of China, with China second with 19.2%.

Giant waves damage S Asia economy. Governments, aid agencies, insurers and travel firms are counting the cost of the massive earthquake and waves. Worst-hit areas are Sri Lanka, India, Indonesia and Thailand, with at least 23,000 people killed. Early estimates from the World Bank put the amount of aid needed at about $5bn.

China's economy has expanded by a breakneck 9.5% during 2004, faster than predicted. News may mean more limits on investment and lending as Beijing tries to take the economy off the boil. China raised rates by 0.27 percentage points to 5.8% - its first hike in nine years.

South Korea earmarks 100 trillion won ($96bn) for first six months of 2005. Government's main problems are "slumping consumption and a contraction in the construction industry" It aims to create 400,000 jobs and will focus on infrastructure and home building. Not everyone is convinced the plan will work.

Laura Ashley chief Ainum Mohd-Saaid resigns for personal reasons. She will be replaced by Lillian Tan, a non-executive director of the company. The clothing and home furnishing retailer's shares were down 8.51% to 10.75p in late Thursday morning trading on the London Stock Exchange.

Putin backs state grab for Yukos' key production unit by state-owned oil firm Rosneft. Putin said it was quite within the rights of a company to ensure its interests were met. Move amounts to the renationalisation of major chunk of Russia's booming oil industry. The Russian government put the company's Yuganskneftegas subsidiary up for sale.

Tsunami slows Sri Lanka's growth by one percentage point this year. President Kumaratunga appeals for peace and national unity. International Labour Organisation says at least one million people have lost their livelihoods. Norway's peace negotiator Erik Solheim due to arrive on Wednesday to try to revive peace talks.

Monsanto fined $1.5m for bribery of Indonesian official. Agrochemical firm paid $50,000 bribe to avoid environmental impact studies. Firm also admitted to paying bribes to a number of other high-ranking officials between 1997 and 2002. Monsanto also agreed to three years' close monitoring of its business practices.

The World Trade Organisation is to end its Multi-Fibre Agreement (MFA) on midnight of 31 December. Christian Aid condemned the move, saying it would see almost a million jobs in Bangladesh alone being axed. Supporters of the change claim it will mean increased efficiency and lower costs for Western consumers.

European leaders say Asian states must let their currencies rise against the US dollar to ease pressure on the euro. White House approval for the weaker greenback has helped trigger the move. China is seen as the main culprit, with exports soaring up 35% in 2004 partly on back of a currency pegged to the dollar.

Anil Ambani, vice-chairman of India Petrochemicals Limited (IPCL), stayed away from a gathering of senior managers on Thursday. The move follows a decision earlier this month by Anil to resign from his post. His resignation was not accepted by his brother, who is also the boss of IPCL.

Chinese exports rise 25% in 2004 over the previous year. Spurt puts China's trade surplus at a six-year high. It may also increase pressure on China to relax the peg joining its currency, the yuan, with the weakening dollar. The peg is often blamed by US lawmakers for job losses at home.

Fosters bought 18.8% of Southcorp, the global winemaker behind the Penfolds, Lindemans and Rosemount brands. SouthCorp confirmed the brewer had asked for talks. Both firms asked the Sydney stock market to suspend trading until Monday.

Brazil plays down claims that it could step in to save the country's biggest airline. Varig is struggling under a huge debt burden of an estimated debt of 6.5 billion reais ($2.3bn or £1.2bn) The airline could also win a sizeable windfall from a compensation claim against the government.

Deutsche Bank says Yukos has few Texas ties beyond bank accounts and a Texas-based finance chief. The bank says the Russian oil giant has artificially manufactured a legal case to stop the sale of its main asset. It had wanted to help fund Gazprom's plans for a $10bn bid for Yuganskneftegas.

Israeli economy picking up pace. Exports for the year rose by 14%, while tourist revenues were up by 30%. Imports gained by 13%, signalling that domestic demand has picked up again. In 2003, the economy expanded by 1.3%, according to the statistical office.

US mortgage company Fannie Mae should restate its earnings, watchdogs say. Move is likely to put a billion-dollar dent in its accounts, SEC says. SEC accuses firm of using techniques that 'did not comply in material respects' Freddie Mac restated earnings by $5bn (£2.6bn) after a probe of its books.

Economists believe several of the 10 countries hit by the giant waves could see a slowdown in growth. Governments are expected to take steps, such as cutting taxes and increasing spending, to facilitate a recovery. Rapid rebuilding will be key to limiting the impact. At least 25,000 people dead, with Sri Lanka, Thailand, India and Indonesia worst hit.

Gazprom took over nuclear fuel giant Atomstroieksport in October 2004. Most of the taxes claimed are linked to the company's export activity. Claims for back-taxes was a tool used against Yukos, and led to its enforced sale. Some analysts fear the Kremlin will continue to use these sort of moves to boost its efforts to regain control over strategically important sectors.

Euronext has approached the London Stock Exchange (LSE) about a possible takeover bid. LSE saw its shares surge 4.9% to a new high of 583p in early trade, following the announcement. Last week, the group rejected a £1.3bn ($2.5bn) takeover offer from Deutsche Boerse.

Fannie Mae forced to restate $4.4bn in profits. Fannie's profits have been cut by $1.2bn. The company is the second largest in the US after Freddie Mac. It is also the largest provider of mortgage loans to the U.S.

Oil rebounds from weather effect on New York on milder winter weather. A barrel of light crude ended Monday down $1.33 to $42.12. In London, trading of Brent crude was suspended for a public holiday. Despite a fall of more than $12 a barrel from record highs reached in late October, the price of crude oil remains almost 30% higher than year-ago levels.

Chile's copper industry registered record earnings of $14.2bn in 2004. Strong demand from China's fast-growing economy and high prices have fuelled production. Industry expects to see investment worth $10bn over the next three years. BHP Billiton planning to invest $1.9bn between now and 2007.

US trade deficit widens by more than expected in October. The trade shortfall was $55.5bn (£29bn), up 9% from September. Imports rose by 3.4%, while exports increased by only 0.6%. A weaker dollar also increased the cost of imports, though this should help drive export demand.

Minister hits out at Yukos sale and calls for renationalisation of energy industry. German Gref says direct state involvement in oil was "unjustified" Comments follow sale of much of oil giant YukOS to cover back taxes. Sale effectively took most of firm's assets into public ownership.

Air Jamaica has been hit by high fuel costs and the 11 September attacks. The company will be restructured with the aim of finding a new buyer. Air Jamaica transports about 55% of all passengers to the island. Its pilots are reportedly among the best paid in the industry, with senior members of staff earning in excess of $234,000 a year.

Dollar hovers around record lows against the euro on Friday. Concern grows about the size of the US budget deficit. Bush administration's apparent unwillingness to intervene to support the dollar has caused further concern. Trading has been volatile over the past week because of technical and automated trading and light demand.

UK economy grew by an estimated 3.1% in 2004 after accelerating in the last quarter of the year, says the Office for National Statistics. The annual figure marked out the best year since 2000, and was also well ahead of 2.2% recorded in 2003. Growth in final three months of 2004 marked the 50th consecutive quarters of expansion.

Glazer makes new approach to buy Manchester United. US tycoon has been wooing the club for the last 12 months. Mr Glazer has already had one takeover attempt turned down by the Red Devils. He used his 28.1% shareholding to vote off three board members last November.

Madagascar has completed the replacement of its Malagasy franc with a new currency. The ariary was the name of a pre-colonial currency in the Indian Ocean island state. It was trading at 1,893 to the US dollar on Monday. A central bank official said the move was symbolic of the country's independence.

Nortel in $300m profit revision after an audit which led to the sacking of the Canadian firm's chief. Figures showed revenue was about 4% higher than first thought. Nortel shares, which have lost nearly 50% of their value since last year, climbed 1.46% in Toronto on Tuesday.

Conference Board survey of 5,000 households points to renewed optimism about job creation and economic growth. US retailers have reported strong sales over the past 10 days after a slow start to the crucial festive season. Wal-Mart, the largest US retailer, has said its December sales are expected to be better than previously forecast.

Iran budget seeks state sell-off of 20% of the state's corporate holdings. Mohammad Khatami's second term as president ends on 1 August, making this his last budget. Opposition from members of parliament who have attacked previous privatisations could block his plans. He predicted economic growth of 7.1% in 2005-6, up from 6.7% this year.

Virgin Blue shares plummet 20% after it warns of a steep fall in full year profits. Virgin Blue, which is 25% owned by Richard Branson, has been struggling to fend off pressure from rival Jetstar. Sydney-listed VirginBlue's shares recovered slightly to close 12% down on Wednesday.

Parmalat collapsed in December 2003 after it emerged that the 4bn euros ($5.2bn; £2.8bn) it supposedly held in a Bank of American offshore account did not in fact exist. The bank, and Italaudit - formerly the Italian arm of auditor Grant Thornton - face lawsuits and possible prosecution.

Air Deccan has signed a deal to acquire 36 planes from Avions de Transport Regional (ATR) The value of the deal has not been revealed, because of a confidentiality clause in the agreement. India's first low-cost airline recently ordered 30 Airbus A320 planes for $1.8bn.

Retail sales rose 0.6% on the month and 6.1% in November. Analysts had expected sales to fall slightly as shoppers put off buying Christmas presents until December. Aggressive tactics, such as one-day discount sales adopted by stores like Marks & Spencer, appear to have paid off.

Yukos unit fetches $9bn at auction in Moscow. Baikal Finance Group outbid favourite Gazprom, the state-controlled gas monopoly, to buy Yuganskneftegas. Yukos reacted immediately by repeating its view that the auction was illegal in international and Russian law.

Businesses fail to plan for HIV/Aids until it affects 20% of people in a country. Report shows concern among businesses has dropped by 23% in the last 12 months. Most (71%) have no policies in place to address the disease. The issue will be highlighted to business and world leaders at the World Economic Forum.

Diageo to buy US wine firm Chalone for $260m (£134m) in an all-cash deal. The world's biggest spirits company already has a US winemaking arm. Diageso said it expects to get US regulatory approval for the deal during the first quarter of 2005.

ISM index of national manufacturing activity rose to 58.6 last month from 57.8 in November. The result for December was slightly better than analysts' expectations and the 19th consecutive expansion. ISM said the growth was driven by a "significant" rise in the new orders.

Venezuela identifies more than 500 farms, including 56 large estates. A further 40,000 farms are yet to be inspected, the state's National Land Institute says. Critics of the land reform policy claim president Hugo Chavez is trying to enforce a communist-style economic programme that ignores property rights.

Ukraine has agreed to pay 30% more for natural gas supplied by Turkmenistan. The deal was sealed three days after Turkmanistan cut off gas supplies in a price dispute that threatened the Ukrainian economy. Supplies from Turkmensistan account for 45% of allnatural gas imported by Ukraine.

News Corp makes $5.4bn Fox offer to minority investors. Follows News Corp's decision to register its business in the US. Fox Entertainment Group generated revenues of $12bn last year. News Corporation shares fell 25 cents to $17.65 after the share offer was announced.

Cairn shares slump on oil setback and possible tax demands. Shares closed down 247p, or 18%, at 1115 pence. Investors had piled into the company after it announced significant oil finds in India this year. Its Mangala field, thought to contain a billion barrels, is its biggest find to date.

Police detain three top executives at milk firm Yili. Reports suggest they are being investigated for embezzlement. The company has been the subject of intense media speculation. Its shares were suspended on Tuesday, having fallen by 10% on Monday. It may now move to oust chairman Zheng Junhuai.

Yukos has filed for bankruptcy protection in the US in an attempt to halt the forced sale of its main production arm. Russian authorities are due to auction off Yuganskneftegas on 19 December to pay a huge tax bill sent to Yukos. As the firm is based in Russia and has no significant US assets, lawyers are unsure of the outcome. Analysts believe that if its production unit is auctioned off, it is likely to be bought up by a government-backed firm.

Irish company hit by Iraqi report.Shares in Irish oil company Petrel Resources have lost more than 50% of their value on a report that the firm has failed to win a contract in Iraq.Reuters news agency reported that Iraq's Oil Ministry has awarded the first post-war oilfield contracts to a Canadian and a Turkish company.

BBC poll indicates economic gloom. Most respondents also said their national economy was getting worse. But when asked about their own family's financial outlook, a majority said they were positive about the future. Almost 23,000 people in 22 countries were questioned for the poll, which was mostly conducted before the Asian tsunami disaster.

Bernie Ebbers, 63, is accused of being the mastermind behind an $11bn (£6bn) accounting fraud. His indictment includes charges of securities fraud, conspiracy and filing false reports with regulators. If found guilty, he could face a substantial jail sentence. Under his leadership, WorldCom emerged from Mississippi obscurity to become a $160bn telecoms giant.

Dollar hits new low versus euro at $1.364 per euro. The US is struggling with a ballooning trade deficit. Analysts predict that the dollar is likely to fall even further. It has lost 7% this year, while against the Japanese yen it is down 3.2%.

Nasdaq Stock Market plans to raise $100m (£52m) from the sale. Some observers see this as another step closer to a full public listing. The Nasdaq is made up shares in technology firms and other companies with high growth potential. It was the most potent symbol of the 1990s internet and telecoms boom.

Christmas shoppers flock to tills on last Saturday before Christmas. Manchester's Trafford Centre said it was "the biggest Christmas to date" Regent Street Association said shops in central London were expecting the "best Christmas ever" Reports of a slump in pre-Christmas sales were related to the growing popularity of internet sales.

GM in crunch talks on Fiat future on Tuesday. Fiat claims that GM is legally obliged to buy the 90% of the car unit it does not already own. GM says the contract, signed in 2000, is no longer valid. Both companies want to cut costs as car industry adjusts to waning demand.

Wal-Mart fights back at accusers with 100 full page adverts in national newspapers. Meanwhile, drugs group Eli Lilly is planning a campaign against "false" claims about its product Prozac. Company president Lee Scott says it is time for the public to hear the "unfiltered truth"

Parmalat has sued 45 banks as it tries to reclaim money paid to banks before the scandal-hit Italian dairy company went bust last year. The firm collapsed with debts of about 14bn euros ($19bn; £10bn) New boss Enrico Bondi has already taken legal action against a number of lenders.

Air Deccan was set up last year and wants to lure travellers away from the railway network and pricier rivals. India has a population of more than a billion people and many observers feel that it is underserved by airlines. The potential of the Indian market has attracted attention at home and abroad.

News Corp is "kicking the tires of pretty much all video games companies" Santa Monica-based Activison is said to be one firm on its takeover list. Video games are "big business" and News Corp "would like to get into it", says chief operating officer Peter Chernin.

Delta Air Lines is cutting domestic fares by as much as 50% as part of a plan to ensure its financial survival. Other US carriers, including United, have sought bankruptcy protection, amid high fuel costs and competition from discount carriers. Delta, which lost $646m in the three months to September, was forced to cut 6,900 jobs.

Japan's economic growth will slow to 1.6% in the next fiscal year starting in April 2005. Deflation - or falling consumer prices - has plagued Japan for more than five years. Bank of Japan has regularly flooded the money market with excess cash to keep short term interest rates at 0%.

Lung cancer drug did not significantly prolong survival in patients with the disease. This setback for the group follows the rejection by the US in October of its anti-coagulant pill Exanta. Meanwhile, cholesterol drug Crestor is facing mounting safety concerns. AztraZeneca has now appointed a new executive director to the board.

EuroDisney to sell 253m euros (£175m; $328m) of new shares as it looks to avoid insolvency. The sale is the last part of a plan to restructure 2.4bn euros-worth of debts. Despite struggling since it was opened in 1992, EuroDisney has recently made progress in turning its business around.

Mitsubishi Motors in talks with French carmaker PSA Peugeot Citroen. Company has been hit by a recall scandal and the withdrawal of support from shareholder DaimlerChrysler. Sales have slid 41% in the past year, catalysed by the revelation that the company had systematically been hiding records of faults.

Wipro offers services such as call centres to foreign clients. Firm has worked for more than half of the companies on the Fortune 500 list. Third-quarter sales rose 34% to 20.9bn rupees. 90% of employees at its business process outsourcing operations had had to be replaced.

British Chamber of Commerce says UK manufacturing sector will continue to face "serious challenges" over the next two years. Group's quarterly survey of companies found exports had picked up in the last three months of 2004. Employment in manufacturing also fell and job expectations were at their lowest level for a year. The outlook for the service sector was "uncertain"

2,000 business and political leaders from around the globe will listen to UK Prime Minister Tony Blair's opening speech on Wednesday. Earlier in the day came an update on efforts to have 3 million people on anti-Aids drugs by the end of 2005. Anti-globalisation campaigners have called off a demonstration planned for the weekend.

Luxury goods group LVMH has sold its loss-making Christian Lacroix clothing label to a US investment group. The Paris-based firm has been shedding non-core businesses and focusing on its most profitable brands including Moet & Chandon champagne and Louis Vuitton. Falic group said it planned to expand the brand by opening new stores.

Executive trio leave Aer Lingus early on 28 January. Chief executive Willie Walsh, chief financial officer Brian Dunne and chief operations officer Seamus Kearney. They announced in November they would quit in May, but did not give a reason. The three have refused to confirm reports they plan to launch a private airline.

UK house prices dipped slightly in November, the Office of the Deputy Prime Minister said. Average house price fell marginally to £180,226, from £18,444 in October. Bank of England said the number of mortgages approved in the UK has fallen to the lowest level for nearly a decade.

Cuts will affect about 9% of 55,000 staff of the combined companies. Oracle's 18-month fight to acquire Peoplesoft was one of most drawn-out and hard-fought US takeover battles of recent times. The merged companies are set to be a major force in the enterprise software market.

Spending on credit and debit cards has overtaken cash spending in the UK for the first time. The moment that plastic toppled cash happened at 10.38am on Wednesday, according to the Association for Payment Clearing Services (Apacs) Apacs chose school teacher Helen Carroll, from Portsmouth, to make the historic transaction.

BA to suspend two Saudi services from 27 March. Airline said the decision was a commercial one due to reduced passenger demand. Passengers with flights booked after the suspension date will be contacted by BA for alternative arrangements to be made. It suspended flights to Saudi Arabia for three weeks in autumn 2003 after a government warning.

Inbev to buy Alfa-Eco's stake in Sun Interbrew for up to 259.7m euros ($353.3m; £183.75m) World's biggest beermaker will have near-total control over the Russian brewer. InBev brands include Bass, Stella Artois, Hoegaarden and Staropramen.

Indonesia, which originally accepted the debt moratorium offer, owes the Paris Club about $48bn (£25.5bn) Mr Bakrie said a $1.7bn donors' aid package meant the moratorium was unnecessary. The money was for the rebuilding of Aceh province, badly hit by the tsunami of 26 December.

Financial Economists Roundtable (FER) wants Congress to act. Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation (PBGC) is £23bn in deficit. FER says firms should not have been allowed to reduce the insurance premiums they pay into the PBGC fund. Cash-strapped US companies argued in favour of the 2004 rule change.

Fed warns of more US rate rises in 2005. The clear signal pushed the dollar up to $1.3270 to the euro by 0400 GMT. Dow Jones index dropped almost 100 points on Tuesday, with the Nasdaq also falling as key tech stocks were hit by broker downgrades.

More than 2,000 business and political leaders from around the globe are arriving in the Swiss mountain resort. Anti-globalisation campaigners have called off a demonstration planned for the weekend. The Brazilian city of Porto Alegre will host the rival World Social Forum, timed to run in parallel with the WEF's ritzier event in Davos.

India to allow long-distance air travel to Saudi Arabia and UAE. The move is part of an effort to make the country more competitive in the global air transport market. It is the first time since the 1980s that the U.S. has been allowed to do so.

US retail sales rise 1.2% in December, up from 0.1% a month earlier. Sales climbed 8% for the year, the best performance since an 8.5% rise in 1999. The gains were led by a 4.3% jump in auto sales as dealers used enhanced offers to get cars out of showrooms.

French co-head of European defence and aerospace group EADS Philippe Camus is to leave his post. Airbus head Noel Forgeard is now set to replace him, bringing the company's power struggle to an end. The company recently came under pressure as it became clear that the A380 superjumbo was running over budget. Rainer Hertrich will also step down when his contract expires next year.

SEC asks for information about transactions involving holders of 5% or more of the firm's shares. Marsh is also the focus of an inquiry the New York attorney-general into whether insurers rigged the market. Since that inquiry was launched in October, Marsh has replaced its chief executive and held a boardroom shake-out.

Green groups say putting pressure on supply chains is a major way companies can reduce their environmental impact. Less than a quarter of companies get their corporate social responsibility (CSR) reports independently verified. The UK government will soon require all companies to report their social and environmental risks in their annual reports.

Bank of China is one of two frontrunners in the race to list overseas. China's banking sector is burdened with at least $190bn of bad debt. Attempts to strengthen internal controls and tighten lending policies have uncovered a succession of scandals involving embezzlement by bank officials.

LSE'sets date for takeover deal' by the end of the month, Sunday Telegraph reports. Both Deutsche Boerse and Euronext held talks with the London market last week. A £1.3bn offer from the German exchange has already been rejected.

Job creation was one of last year's main concerns for the US economy. While worries still remain, the conditions are set for steady growth in 2005. Unemployment rate stayed at 5.4% in December, and about 200,000 jobs will need to be created each month if that figure is to drop.

Next's shares fell more than 3% following the release of the trading statement. Chief executive Simon Wolfson admitted that festive sales were "below where we would expect a normal Christmas to be" Next's like-for-like store sales in the five months from 3 August to 24 December were up 2.9%.

Traders at US banking giant Citigroup are facing a criminal investigation in Germany over a controversial bond deal. Deal saw the sale of 11bn euros ($14.4bn; £7.6bn) of government bonds in a few minutes on 2 August. The move was widely criticised at the time, and now the German regulator says it has found evidence of possible market manipulation.

Dow Jones closes more than 1% higher at 10,137, while Nasdaq rises 0.9% to 2,004. Many investors believe that Mr Bush's policies are more business-friendly than those of his Democrat challenger, John Kerry. Higher share prices also reflect relief that a clear winner has emerged from what proved to be a tight poll.

ECB holds rates amid growth fears. High oil prices, meanwhile, have put upward pressure on the inflation rate. Inflation in the eurozone, however, is estimated at about 2.3% in December, above ECB guidelines of 2%. ECB President Jean-Claude Trichet remains upbeat about prospects for the region.

IMF agrees fresh Turkey funding deal. Turkey's current $18.6bn loan agreement with the IMF expires in February. New deal would see it receive added support between 2005 and 2007. In return for the funding, Turkey would be expected to keep inflation under control and introduce market reforms.

Aguas Argentinas, controlled by France's Suez, wants a tariff rise of 60% to fund water-supply improvements. Planning Minister Julio De Vido has offered State help but not for "free" He has said a contribution could be made in return for a seat on the company's board.

American Airlines' parent AMR reported a loss of $387m (£206m) for the fourth quarter of 2004. Southwest Airlines saw its fourth-quarter 2004 profits fall 15% to $56m, against $66m a year earlier. Both said high fuel bills would continue to pressure revenues in 2005.

India's biggest carmaker Maruti has reported a sharp increase in quarterly profit after a booming economy and low interest rates boosted demand. Net profit surged 70% to 2.39bn rupees ($54.98m; £29.32m) in the last three months of 2004. Total sales were 30.1bn Rupees, up 27% from the same period.

Yukos will return to a US court on Wednesday to seek sanctions against Baikal Finance Group, the little-known firm which has bought its main asset. Yukos' US lawyers will attempt to have Baikkal assets frozen after the Russian government ignored a U.S court order last week blocking the sale.

Emilio Botin is the chairman of Spain's most powerful bank, Santander Central Hispano. He is accused of misusing the bank's funds after he approved the payment of 160m euros in bonus and pension payouts to two former executives. The trial was suspended when his lawyer introduced a new set of documents on the day testimony was set to begin.

Iran's bid to join the trade body has been refused after the US blocked its application for the 21st time. The countries stand to reap huge benefits from membership of the group, whose purpose is to promote free trade. Joining, however, is a lengthy process and China's admission in 2001 took 15 years.

Light crude oil futures fell $2.86 to $41.32 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange. US crude is still 30% more expensive than at the beginning of 2004, boosted by growing demand and bottlenecks at refineries. London's International Petroleum Exchange remained closed for the Christmas holiday.

Trade in April-July rose to $186.3m (£97m) from $64.4m in the same period in 2003. Figures represent less than 1% of India's overall exports. But business is expected to be boosted further from 2006 when the South Asian Free Trade Area Agreement starts.

Stanley Fischer, vice chairman of banking giant Citigroup, has agreed to take the Bank of Israel job subject to approval from parliament and cabinet. His nomination by Prime Minister Ariel Sharon came as a surprise, and led to gains on the Tel Aviv stock market. Mr Fischer will have to become an Israeli citizen to taking the job. The US says he will not haveto give up US citizenship to do so.

China has ordered a halt to construction work on 26 big power stations. The State Environmental Protection Agency said the projects had failed to do proper environmental assessments. Topping the list was a controversial dam on the scenic upper Yangtze River. Other projects included a petrochemicals plant and a port in Fujian.

Retail sales dropped by 1% on the month in December, after a 0.6% rise in November. Clothing retailers and non-specialist stores were the worst hit with only internet retailers showing any significant growth. The last time retailers endured a tougher Christmas was 23 years previously, when sales plunged 1.7%.

S&N will buy a 17.5% equity stake in United, maker of the well-known Kingfisher lager brand. A similar holding will be controlled by Vijay Mallya, chair of Indian firm. The deal was a "natural development" of its joint venture with United.

SSL refuses to comment on'market speculation' Financial Times report says business intelligence firm GPW is starting due diligence work on SSL International. Shares in SSL, which also makes Scholl footwear, up more than 6%, or 16.75 pence to 293.5p. Analysts have seen SSL as a takeover target for years.

GE sees 'excellent' world economy and is in 'great shape' General Electric is the US' biggest firm based on stock market valuation. The group forecast sustained growth at between 10-15% for this year and next. GE shares rose 1% on the news before ending Friday 0.24% lower.

Beijingers fume over parking fees that can cost up to 250% more than outdoor parking. Officials may scrap the relatively cheap hourly fee near sports grounds and impose a higher flat rate during matches. Chinese authorities are building dozens of new roads to create a showcase modern city ahead of the 2008 Olympic Games.

Creditors of South Korea's top credit card firm have said they will put the company into liquidation if its ex-parent firm fails to back a bail-out. LG Card's creditors have given LG group until Wednesday to sign up to a $1.1bn rescue package.LG Group has said any package should reflect the firm's new ownership.

Shares in Cairn Energy rose 3.8% to 1,088 pence on Tuesday. UK firm announced a fresh gas discovery in northern India. Firm last year made a number of other new finds in the Rajasthan area. Chief executive Bill Gammell cautioned that additional evalution was first needed.

Ford gains from finance not cars. Fourth quarter turnover was $44.7bn, compared to $45.9bn a year ago. Total company vehicle unit sales in 2004 were 6,798,000. Ford declined to provide guidance for first quarter 2005. It will do so at a presentation in New York on 26 January.

Reliance unit loses Anil Ambani. Reliance's operations have massive reach, covering textiles, telecommunications, petrochemicals, petroleum refining and marketing. The brothers' spat has hogged headlines in India during recent weeks, despite a denial from the family that there was anything wrong.

Continental shares fall 6.87% to $10.44 by 1830 GMT. Airline warns of 'inadequate liquidity' if it fails to reduce wage costs by $500m by the end of February. Failure to make cutbacks may also push it to reduced its fleet, group says.

Channel Tunnel operator Eurotunnel has seen sales fall in the face of the upsurge in European low-cost airlines. The firm said sales were down 4% in 2004 to 789m euros ($1.03bn; £548m) Income from vehicle-carrying shuttle services fell 7%, although 15% more passengers meant a 2% rise in railway revenue.

Swiss Re says 2004 is most expensive year on record for property insurers. Property claims reach $42bn (£21.5bn) 95% of insurance claims were for natural catastrophes, with the rest attributed to made-made events. The largest claims came from the US, which was struck by four hurricanes, and Japan.

Libya takes $1bn in unfrozen funds from the US. The original size of Libya's funds was $400m, the central bank says. US ban on trade and economic activity with Tripoli was suspended in April. It was imposed by then president Ronald Regan in 1986 after a series of terrorist acts.

Krispy Kreme shares hit $10.48 on the news. Firm warned the move would cut its profits by $3.8m to $4.9m. It also warned it might have to further restate results for 2004 and 2005. The firm is currently facing Securities and Exchange Commission investigation of its accounts.

Six foreign-owned textile factories have closed in Lesotho, leaving 6,650 garment workers jobless. Factory Workers Union secretary general Billy Macaefa blamed the closures on the end of worldwide textile quotas. The quotas for developing nations, ended on 1 January, gave them a set share of the rich countries' markets.

US economy still growing says Fed says in latest Beige Book report. Consumer spending was higher in December than November, and festive sales were also up on 2003. Labour markets firmed in a number of districts, but wage pressures generally remained modest, report says. Office leasing was especially brisk in Washington DC and New York City, it adds.

Mixed Christmas for US retailers. Nordstrom said same store sales were 9.3% higher than during the same period last year. Trendy youth labels also sold well, with sales jumping 28% at young women's clothing retailer Bebe Stores. But Wal-Mart only saw its sales rise after it cut prices.

The Open Society Institute (OSI) has accused Kazakhstan officials of trying to close down its local office. A demand for unpaid taxes and fines of $600,000 is politically motivated, the OSI claimed. The organisation has found itself in trouble after being accused of helping to topple Georgia's former president.

Sales totalled 3.9 million units worldwide during 2004, the company said at the Detroit Motor Show. A switch to new models hit luxury marque Mercedes-Benz. Chrysler avoided the fate of US rivals Ford and General Motors, both of whom lost ground to Japanese firms.

WMC Resources says it is worth up to 30% more than a hostile 7.4bn Australian dollar ($5.8bn; £3bn) bid by rival Xstrata. There is now pressure on Swiss-based XStrata to increase its takeover offer. WMC chairman Tommie Bergman said in a statement the directors believed it was in shareholders' best interest to reject the bid.

UK children use "pester power" to get their parents to stump up nearly a third of this income. The bulk of their cash goes on personal care, soft drinks and food. British teenage girls are the most keen to use make-up products, compared to their counterparts in seven European countries.

LG Card has seven million customers and its collapse would have sent shockwaves through the country's economy. A consortium of creditors and LG Group, a family owned conglomerate, have each put up $480m to stabilise the firm. South Korea's consumer credit market has been slowly recovering from a crisis in 2002 when a credit bubble burst.

US industrial output growth eases to 0.3% in November. Analysts say if the carmaking sector had been excluded the data would have been more impressive. The increase in production comes on the heels of news of a recovery in retail sales. US economy grew at a respectable annual rate of 3.7% between July and September.

Wal-Mart agrees to pay $14.5m to settle a lawsuit over gun sales violations in California. Lawsuit alleged Wal-mart committed thousands of violations between 2000 and 2003. Total payment includes $5million in fines and more than $4million to fund state compliance checks with gun laws.

The company has been fractious since founder Dhirubhai Ambani died in 2002. The company plans to buy back 52 million shares at 570 rupees (£6.80; $13) Each share will be bought back at a premium of more than 10% to its current market price.

Indy buys into India paper Jagran in a deal worth 25m euros ($34.1m) News of the deal came as the group announced that its results would meet market forecasts. The company reported strong revenue growth across all its major markets. Group made no comment about the future of Independent newspaper.

China's economy expanded by a breakneck 9.5% during 2004. The news may mean more limits on investment and lending as Beijing tries to take the economy off the boil. China has sucked in raw materials and energy to feed its expansion, which could have knock-on effects on the rest of the world if it overheats.

Job creation was one of last year's main concerns for the US economy. While worries still remain, the conditions are set for steady growth in 2005. Unemployment rate stayed at 5.4% in December, and about 200,000 jobs will need to be created each month if that figure is to drop.

Bob Murray, chairman of Sunderland FC, has launched a £1.5m ($2.8m) bid for the club. Mr Murray is already Sunderland's leading shareholder, holding a 37.6% stake. He agreed to buy BSkyB's 4.76% holding in the Wearside club on Tuesday.

Business confidence dips in Japan for the first time since March 2003. Slower economic growth, rising oil prices, a stronger yen and weaker exports blamed. Japan's economy grew by just 0.1% in the three months to September, according to revised data. But Japanese firms have been stepping up capital investment.

EC calls truce in deficit battle with France and Germany. Under EU rules, member countries must keep their deficits below 3%. Germany and France will breach that this year. It will be the third year in a row that the two countries have broken the European Union's Stability and Growth Pact rules.

Kraft's new advertising policy is aimed at children between the ages of six and 11. The largest US food maker will also add a label to its more nutritional and low-fat brands to promote the benefits. Move comes as the firms face criticism from consumer groups concerned at rising levels of obesity in US children.

New vehicle sales jumped 22% to 449,603 from a year earlier. Strong economic growth and low interest rates have driven demand. NAAMSA said it expects sales to top 500,000 in 2005. The vehicle industry accounts for about 13% of South Africa's total exports.

Iraqi voters turn to economic issues ahead of Sunday's election. Unemployment, poor social services and poverty made worse by a lack of investment. Some progress has been made thanks to the country's oil revenues which have exceeded $22bn since June 2003. But the growing divide between haves and have-nots is angering voters.

Barclays shares up on merger talk. UK banking icon Barclays was founded more than 300 years ago. It has operations in over 60 countries and employs 76,200 staff worldwide. Wells Fargo had net income of $6.2bn in its last financial year, a 9% increase on previous year.

UK-based bank Standard Chartered said it would spend $3.3bn (£1.8bn) to buy one of South Korea's main retail banks. Move would be the South Korean financial sector's biggest foreign takeover. KFB has 3 million retail customers, 6% of the country's banking market and extensive branch network.

Bush to get 'tough' on deficit in bid to halve the country's deficit. US budget and its trade deficit are both deep in the red. Mr Bush indicated there would be "strict discipline" on non-defence spending. The vow to cut the deficit had been one of his re-election declarations.

UK economy could suffer a backlash from the slowdown in the housing market. Deloitte is forecasting economic growth of 2% this year, below Chancellor Gordon Brown's forecast of 3% to 3.5%. It also believes that interest rates will fall to 4% by the end of the year.

US budget deficit to reach $368bn this year, officials said on Tuesday. Past Congressional Budget Office forecasts said there would be a $348bn shortfall in the 2005 fiscal year. In November, the gap between US exports and imports widened to more than $60bn, a record figure.

Quiksilver said to be considering an offer for Rossignol. Nike and K2 have previously been mentioned as possible suitors. European sporting goods companies have seen foreign revenues squeezed by a slump in the value of the US dollar, making a takeover more attractive. Companies such as Quikilver would be able to cut costs by selling RossIGNol skis through their shops.

Boeing secures giant Japan order for up to 50 7E7 planes. Deal could be worth as much as $6bn (£3.1bn) for the US giant. Airbus this week announced the first pre-sale of its A350 aircraft. Boeing has orders for 56 of the aircraft so far.

Research group JD Power estimates sales will hit 200,000 in 2005. Toyota has led the market to date with the Prius, popularised by a number of celebrities keen to burnish their "green" credentials. Ford is bringing a hybrid SUV - the Mariner - to market a year ahead of schedule with plans for three more models by 2008.

Richard Scrushy, 52, is accused of "directing" a $2.7bn accounting fraud. He is the first chief executive to be tried for breaching the Sarbanes Oxley Act. The law was introduced in the wake of the Enron and WorldCom frauds. Several former HealthSouth employees have already pleaded guilty.

Amex shares up on spin-off news. American Express Financial Advisors has more than 12,000 advisers selling financial advice, funds and insurance to 2.5 million customers. Analysts estimate that a stand-alone AEFA could have a market value of $10bn (£5.3bn)

Winemaker rejects Foster's offer worth 3.1bn Australian dollars ($2.3bn; £1.8bn) Southcorp, whose brands include Penfolds, Rosemount and Lindemans, dismissed the offer as inadequate. A merger would create a global player with worldwide annual sales of 39m cases.

10 former WorldCom directors agree to pay $54m, including $18m from their own pockets, to settle a class action lawsuit. The remaining $36m will be paid by the directors' insurers. A formal agreement is expected to be signed on Thursday in a US district court in Manhattan.

World's two biggest reinsurers say exposure will be less than for other disasters. Rebuilding costs are likely to be cheaper than in developed countries. At least 10 countries have been affected, with Sri Lanka, Indonesia, India and Thailand among the worst hit. Tourists cutting short their holidays in affected areas may suffer a financial impact.

Shares in Deutsche Boerse have risen more than 3% after a shareholder fund voiced opposition to the firm's planned takeover of the London Stock Exchange. Opposition from TCI has fuelled speculation that the proposed takeover could fail. Rival exchange operator Euronext has also said it may bid for the LSE.

Egypt and Israel seal trade deal with the US. Deal allows Egyptian goods made in partnership with Israeli firms free access to American markets. There has been deep sensitivity in Egypt about any form of co-operation with Israel as long as its peace process with Palestinians remains blocked. But in recent weeks an unusual warmth has crept into relations between the two countries.

Asia shares defy post-quake gloom. Indonesian, Indian and Hong Kong stock markets reach record highs. Investors do not fear a major economic impact. Full economic costs of the disaster remain unclear. But some economists have said that as much as 1% of annual growth may be lost.

The pipeline will run from the Bulgarian port of Burgas, over the Black Sea to the Albanian city of Vlore on the Adriatic coast. It aims to transport 750,000 daily barrels of oil. The project was conceived in 1994 but it was delayed because of the lack of political support.

Financial details of the deal were not disclosed. Sale includes nearby Simpson's in the Strand restaurant. Irish-based property firm Quinlan Private bought the Savoy along with the Berkeley, Claridge's and the Connaught for £750m last year. Prince Alwaleed bin Talal's hotel investments include the luxury George V in Paris.

Swiss cement firm Holcim has bid $800m (£429m) to buy two Indian cement firms and a holding company in the country. Shares in ACC fell 5.5% as investors, who thought the offer was underpriced, decided to sell. Meanwhile, UK-based firm Aggregate Industries said it had agreed a £1.8bn takeover.

Guidant is a key producer of equipment that combats heart problems. Deal is aimed at offsetting Johnson & Johnson's reliance on a slowing drug business. Analysts say that more mergers are likely because the drug and healthcare industries are fragmented and under pressure to cut costs.

Bank holds interest rate at 4.75% in a widely-predicted move. Recent data has indicated a slowdown in manufacturing and consumer spending. Retail sales disappointed over Christmas, with analysts putting the drop down to less consumer confidence. The Bank remains concerned about the long-term risks posed by personal debt.

German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder has called for radical reform of the EU's stability pact. He said existing fiscal rules should be loosened to allow countries to run deficits above the current 3% limit if they meet certain criteria. Changes to the pact are due to be agreed at an economic summit in March.

48% of chartered surveyor estate agents reported lower prices in the three months to November - the highest level in 12 years. Number of sales dropped 32% to an average of 22 per surveyors. The amount of unsold properties on their books rose for the sixth month in a row.

Singapore's economy grew by 8.1% in 2004, its best performance since 2000. The advance, the second-fastest in Asia after China, was led by growth in the key manufacturing sector. However, a slower-than-expected fourth quarter points to more modest growth for the trade-driven economy in 2005.

Mikhail Khodorkovsky handed over his entire 59.5% stake in Yukos to Leonid Nevzlin. Mr NevZlin is YukOS' largest shareholder but is living in self-imposed exile in Israel. The sale of Yuganskneftegaz was sold by the Russian authorities to recover tax claims.

Chinese dam firm 'defies Beijing' order to stop work on sister Xiluodu dam. China Three Gorges Project Corp could now face a fine up to £12,700. The company has denied that its projects violated regulations. It is one of 30 large-scale construction projects called to a halt.

Honda must pay 1.47m yuan ($177,600) in compensation. China has threatened sanctions if it fails to clamp down on product piracy. The EU estimates the global trade in pirated wares is worth more than 200bn euros a year (£140bn; $258bn)

Wall Street cool to eBay's profit expectations. Shares in online auction house eBay fell 9.8% in after-hours trade on Wednesday. Despite seeing net profits rise by 44% to $205.4m during October to December, Wall Street had expected more. For 2004 as a whole, eBay earned $778.2m on sales of $3.27bn.

Enron went bankrupt in 2001 after it emerged it had hidden hundreds of millions of dollars in debt. None of the 18 former directors will admit any wrongdoing. Deal is the fourth major settlement negotiated by lawyers who filed a class action on behalf of Enron's shareholders almost three years ago.

Seasonally adjusted jobless total rose 17,000 to 4.483 million. Bad weather and a sluggish economy blamed for rise. News of the rise came as government welfare reforms came into force, a move that is expected to see unemployment swell still further in coming months.

Senior vice president Robert Stearns pleads guilty to scheming to defraud. Offence carries a sentence of 16 months to four years in state prison. Marsh says it will continue to co-operate in the case. Company is also still being examined by US stock market regulator the Securities and Exchange Commission.

The landmark deal could see thousands of people suffering from lung diseases - caused by asbestos the company once made - receive compensation. The move follows angry protests after the firm said a previous compensation fund was running out of money. A subsequent New South Wales state inquiry criticised Hardie's actions.

Gap between US exports and imports has widened to more than $60bn (£31.7bn), an all-time record. Part of the expanding deficit came from high prices for oil imports. Treasury Secretary John Snow put a brave face on the news, saying it was a sign of strong economic expansion.

UK interest rates held at 4.75% in widely-predicted move. Recent data has indicated a slowdown in manufacturing and consumer spending. Retail sales disappointed over Christmas, with analysts putting the drop down to less consumer confidence. CBI chief economist Ian McCafferty said the economy had "slowed in recent months in response to rate rises"

EU to probe Alitalia'state aid' The European Commission has officially launched an in-depth investigation into whether the airline is receiving illegal state aid. The investigation could take up to 18 months but Transport Commissioner Jacques Barrot said he wanted it to be carried out as swiftly as possible.

Watchdog probes Vivendi bond sale. French stock market regulator AMF has filed complaints against the media giant. It believes the prospectus for a bond issue was unclear and that executives may have had privileged information. Deutsche Bank, which was responsible for selling the convertible bonds to investors, could face penalties.

Paul Tellier, who was also Bombardier's president, left the company amid an ongoing restructuring. Laurent Beaudoin, part of the family that controls the Montreal-based firm, will take on the role of CEO under a newly created management structure. Analysts say the resignations seem to have stemmed from a boardroom dispute.

SEC to rethink post-Enron rules to ease burden on foreign firms. William Donaldson promises "several initiatives" in speech at LSE. European firms have protested that US laws make Wall Street listings too costly. Firms that break the new law could face huge fines, while senior executives risk jail terms.

UK house prices increased by 1.1% in December, the first monthly rise since September. Average price of a house in the UK now stands at £162,086, Halifax said. Capital Economics branded Halifax's findings a "temporary surprise," which would be reversed over the coming months.

Indian oil firm eyes Yukos assets. ONGC chairman Subir Raha: "We are in touch with the concerned Russian entities" Indian oil minister Mani Shankar Aiyar: 'It would make great sense for us to build on that' India imports about 70% of its total oil consumption.

Hobbit picture 'four years away' says Lord of the Rings director Peter Jackson. Rights to JRR Tolkien's book are split between two major film studios. Jackson is currently filming a remake of Hollywood classic King Kong. The film-maker recently sued film company New Line Cinema for undisclosed damages over alleged withheld profits.

The Return (Vozvrashchenie) won the BBC Four World Cinema Award. The film tells the story of two adolescent boys who are subjected to a harsh regime. A viewer poll saw Zhang Yimou's martial arts epic Hero emerge as the favourite with 32% of votes cast.

Day-Lewis will be presented with the Berlinale Camera award on 15 February. The honour, awarded since 1986, honours figures in cinema that the festival feels "particularly indebted to" Man to Man, a historical epic starring Kristin Scott Thomas, opens the German festival. A candid documentary about the life and career of singer George Michael, A Different Story, will also be screened.

TV show unites Angolan families separated by nearly 30 years of war. Meeting Point has become one of TV Angola's most watched programmes. Every Friday, people gather in Luanda's Independence Square to record a message in front of the TV cameras, in the hope that a lost relative will see it. Many relatives have been reunited on air.

The band will play in what has been dubbed Europe's biggest tent on Glasgow Green on Tuesday, 14 June. Fans who bought tickets for the original 22 February show can attend the rescheduled concert. The June gig will act as a warm-up for REM's open air concert at Balloch Castle Country Park, on the banks of Loch Lomond, four days later.

Last Star Wars 'not for children' says film-maker George Lucas. He says Revenge of the Sith will be the darkest and most violent film in the series. Lucas predicts the film will get a US rating advising parents some scenes may be unsuitable for under-13s. It opens in UK and US on 19 May.

Frank Capra's 1946 movie starring James Stewart is being turned into a musical. It's a Wonderful Life was based on a short story, The Greatest Gift, by Philip van Doren Stern. Producer Jon Thoday is working with Steve Brown, who wrote the award-winning musical Spend Spend spend.

Comedy sequel Meet the Fockers shot to the top of the UK chart at the weekend. It took £7.2m in three days - eight times more than the number two, Closer. Assault on Precinct 13 was in third. At the same time, US audiences were won over by his new thriller Hide and Seek.

Berlin Film Festival opens on Thursday with period epic Man to Man. More than half of the 21 films in competition for the Golden and Silver Bear awards are from Europe. Festival director Dieter Kosslick says strong showing signals "a new consciousness for European films" Some 350 films will be screened at this year's festival.

Famed music director Viotti dies in Germany at 50. He fell into a coma after suffering a stroke during rehearsals for Jules Massenet's Manon last week. His time at La Fenice coincided with its reopening in 2003 after it was destroyed by fire in 1996.

Johnny Depp is celebrated as one of Hollywood's most maverick talents. He has had a long-running working relationship with the equally unconventional director Tim Burton. His latest role was Peter Pan creator JM Barrie in Finding Neverland. The actor is set to play Willy Wonka in a remake of Roald Dahl's classic Charlie and the Chocolate Factory.

U2 inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in New York. The band, who formed in 1977, are celebrating their 50th anniversary this year. They were joined on stage by the O'Jays, the Pretenders, and the Bee Gees.

Prodigy will join main stage headliners Scissor Sisters and Franz Ferdinand. New Order have joined the T in the Park line-up alongside Athlete and Green Day. The Manchester band will play on 9 July at Scotland's biggest festival. Other bands at the sold-out festival include Queens of the Stone Age.

Fockers keeps US box office lead with total of 204.3m (£109m) Michael Keaton thriller White Noise was second with $24m £12.8m. Martin Scorsese's Howard Hughes biopic The Aviator came third. Lemony Snicket's A Series of Unfortunate Events was fourth.

Rapper 50 Cent scores chart first with three singles in the US top five. Candy Shop remained at the top of the charts, while Disco Inferno crept up from six to 5. He also appears on rap protege The Game's song How We do, now outside the UK top ten.

Singer Ferguson 'facing eviction' from ITV's I'm A Celebrity... Get Me Out Of Here. Bookmakers Ladbrokes says the singer has even odds of being the first contestant to be voted off. Comic Joe Pasquale remains odds on favourite to win the reality show.

Museum to be opened in former recording studio in Los Angeles. A tour bus used by Charles and his entourage over the years will also be on display. Charles won eight Grammy Awards, including album of the year for Genius Loves Company, a collection of duets.

A Different Story will screen in the Panorama section of the Berlin Film Festival. It features the singer talking about both his career and his personal life. Michael will attend the festival to introduce the screening on 16 February. The 93 minute film will see Michael discussing his early days in Wham! along with his later career.

Pop band Busted have had eight top three hits, including four number ones. Frontman Charlie Simpson plans to spend some time working with his other band, Fightstar. The band won best pop act and best breakthrough act at the 2004 Brit Awards. Most recently they topped the charts with the theme from Thunderbirds.

New York rockers top talent poll by BBC News website. The Bravery have been compared to The Cure and New Order. They were the most heavily-tipped act in the survey of 110 impartial critics and broadcasters. Other new artists in this year's list include London indie group Bloc Party at second and UK rapper Kano third.

Fightstar take to the stage at the University of Warwick on Friday night. Charlie Simpson officially announced his departure from pop band Busted. All 1,400 tickets to see Fightstar's first post-Busted live appearance sold out rapidly. They Liked You Better When You Were Dead is due for release in February.

Actress Roberts takes spider role in new film version of children's classic. Oprah Winfrey will voice a goose, John Cleese a sheep and Steve Buscemi a rat. Filming is due to begin in Melbourne, Australia, later this month. Charlotte's Web has sold 45 million copies since it was published in 1952.

Little Britain stars Matt Lucas and David Walliams have been named the most powerful people in TV comedy. The duo kept Phoenix Nights creator Peter Kay at number two and The Office star Ricky Gervais in third place. Newcomers to the annual list included Nighty Night star Julia Davis at seven and Tamsin Greig at 19.

TOTP turns to Elvis impersonator Mario Kombou to sing One Night on Friday's BBC One show. It is his second number one in a row. Presley will feature in the charts for several more months as all 18 of his original UK chart-toppers are reissued.

Cult band Kasabian surge forward with three Brit Award nominations. The four-piece Leicester band blends dark electronics with rock. "British music needs a kick up the arse," says singer Tom Meighan. Their self-titled album was released last September to widespread acclaim.

Beverley Knight and Roni Size have released No More in a bid to reduce gun use. Knight said she was "horrified" by the deaths of Charlene Ellis, 18, and Letisha Shakespeare, 17. Size became involved after two friends, Donna Small and Asha Jama, were shot in his Bristol hometown.

Angels and Demons, by US author Dan Brown, will go on sale on Wednesday. The Da Vinci Code is set in Paris - including the Louvre - and has sold around one million copies in France. Special tours have been organised to trace Robert Langdon's footsteps.

TV presenter Deeley drops CD:UK after six years. The 28-year-old said she wanted to concentrate on new television projects. She will host her last show on 5 March and guest presenters will stand in until a replacement is found. Formerly co-hosted SM:tv alongside Ant and Dec.

download chart debut is delayed until 17 April. BPI wants to create a "level playing field" for independent labels. The US has already merged downloaded singles into its Billboard Hot 100 chart. It is the most significant development in the charts for 20 years, according to the British Phonographic Industry.

Deal to ban 'homophobic' reggae songs struck with gay rights groups. Campaign against stars such as Beenie Man and Sizzla has been waged. Lyrics allegedly call for gay people to be killed or assaulted. The campaign led to gigs being scrapped and a UK police investigation.

The Birmingham-born singer, full name Jamelia Davis, was signed to a record label at the age of 15. She released four number ones from her 2000 album Drama, including the top five hit Money featuring the vocals of reggae artist Beenie Man. In the same year she also fell pregnant and decided to take a break from music.

Stan Lee won a court battle for a slice of the profits from the hit Spider-Man movies. Born in 1922 to poor working-class Jewish immigrants from Romania, Stan Lieberman, got a job in Timely Publications. He was assigned to the comics division and rose to editor by the age of 18. Lee gave each character individual, everyday teenage problems such as dandruff, ingrown toenails and acne.

Nicole Kidman has won a restraining order against two paparazzi photographers. The Oscar-winning star took action against Jamie Fawcett and Ben McDonald. A bugging device was found outside her home earlier this week. Lawyers for the pair denied allegations they had planted the device.

Vera Drake leads UK Oscar hopes with three nominations. Imelda Staunton and Kate Winslet also up for best actress. Clive Owen and Sophie Okonedo nominated for supporting roles in Closer and Hotel Rwanda respectively. UK has two contenders in the best live action short film category.

Bryan Ferry, Phil Manzerana, Andy Mackay and Paul Thompson will take to the stage on the Saturday night of the festival. Morrissey will also play on Saturday, while Supergrass and Idlewild have been confirmed for the Friday. The three-day event takes place from 10-12 June.

German music in a 'zombie' state due to piracy and private copying, says Tim Renner. Music market in Germany peaked in 1997, with sales of 2.6bn euros (£1.8bn) Since 2000, sales have plummeted to just 1.5bn euro (£2.1billion) in 2003.

Douglas set for Indian adventure film Racing The Monsoon. Aishwarya Rai, star of Bride and Prejudice, is the "preferred choice" of the Indian studio. The 60-year-old actor said he hoped to start shooting next year. He said it had been inspired by a Wall Street Journal article.

Supervolcano, a docu-drama about a volcanic eruption in Yellowstone National Park in the US, is among the highlights on the BBC One this winter. The £178m winter schedule also includes the return of Doctor Who and a drama about Angela Cannings, who was wrongly convicted of killing two of her babies. ITV also unveiled their festive season, which includes Stephen Fry in a remake of Tom Brown's Schooldays.

Singer Christina Aguilera is to marry music executive Jordan Bratman. The pair have been together for more than two years. Aguillera burst onto the pop scene in 1999, winning a best new artist Grammy in 2000. Her hits include What a Girl Wants, Dirrty and Beautiful.

US TV host Dick Clark suffers stroke in Los Angeles. The 75-year-old presented long-running show American Bandstand from 1956-87. Clark is scheduled to welcome in the New Year on the ABC network. He is expected to act as executive producer for the upcoming Golden Globe Awards.

Oscar rivals will compete for the international film prize at the ceremony. Other nominees include Bill Condon for Kinsey and Michel Gondry for Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind. The awards will see Eastwood and Scorsese once again competing for directing prize, following last weekend's Oscars.

Ray Charles was a pioneering artist who had a huge influence on the course of rock and pop music. Along with Sam Cooke, he was instrumental in bringing together the gospel fervour of the deep south Baptist church with the "devil's" music of R&B. His songs cast their spell on such 1960s stalwarts as Joe Cocker, Steve Winwood, Eric Burdon and Van Morrison.

Films on war triumph at the Sundance Film Festival in Utah. Why We Fight and The Liberace of Baghdad win top prizes. The film festival has been dominated by themes of war and politics. Last year's winners included The Full Monty and Napoleon Dynamite.

Church urges Nelly show boycott. But a venue spokesman said more than 5,500 tickets had been sold so far. More than 20 Jonesboro ministers urged music fans to boycott the 12 March concert. The Reverend Adrian Rodgers said he was concerned about the rapper's lyrics that include references to drugs, sex and violence.

U2's new album, How To Dismantle An Atomic Bomb, comes 28 years after the band got together in Dublin. The group were born when Mullen put an appeal for bandmates on a high school notice board, attracting fellow pupils Paul Hewson (Bono, vocals), Adam Clayton (bass) and his brother Dick.

BBC says there are no plans for a new series of hit comedy Blackadder. Tony Robinson, who played the servant Baldrick, said Rowan Atkinson was "more keen than he has been in the past" The final series was voted the best farewell episode of a TV series.

New big-screen version of The Magic Roundabout is the latest attempt to turn children's television into box-office gold. He-Man and Transformers will soon receive their own costly makeovers. Critics complain that these expensive takes on iconic series of yesteryear do not match up to our fond memories of the originals.

Goodrem wins top female MTV prize for Neighbours star. Australian Idol runner-up Shannon Noll takes the title of best male. Green Day, the Black Eyed Peas and Missy Higgins take home two awards each. VH1 First Music Award goes to Cher.

Stars pay tribute to actor Ossie Davis at a funeral in New York. Former US president Bill Clinton and singer Harry Belafonte give the eulogy. The 87-year-old was found dead last weekend in his hotel room in Florida. He made his acting debut in 1950 in No Way Out starring Sidney Poiter.

Incredibles win animation awards at Hollywood's Annies ceremony. superhero film named best animated feature. Brad Bird won best director, writer and voice actor for his role as Edna Mode. Shrek 2, which had seven nominations, went home empty-handed. The two movies will compete with Shark Tale in the Oscars at the end of February.

Baywatch was shown in 140 countries at its height. Anna Nicole Smith's reality show and The Dukes of Hazzard were runners-up. Soap operas Knots Landing, Falcon Crest plus The Bold And The Beautiful all made the top 10. The Jerry Springer Show, which came in at sixth on the list, did not fare well.

Mark McClelland had been in the band for more than 10 years. Lead singer Gary Lightbody said: "This is the hardest decision we have ever had to make" Snow Patrol are currently working on the follow-up to their breakthrough third album. The band is set to play support to U2 on a number of summer stadium gigs.

C-Murder, a former member of rap group Tru, was filmed in his orange prison suit for the video for his Y'all Heard of Me single. He is awaiting a second trial after an original conviction was thrown out. Jefferson Parish Sheriff Harry Lee said he was fooled into letting the cameras in. The rapper's lawyer said: "The bottom line is, we didn't do anything wrong"

The soap beat fellow ITV1 show Filthy Love and Channel 4's Shameless. Little Britain was named best comedy while Franz Ferdinand beat Morrissey and The Libertines to the music award. Dead Man's Shoes picked up the best film award, beating Shaun of the Dead and My Summer of Love. The two award ceremonies reflect the achievements the industry believes have been made in the last year.

Connick Jr to lead Broadway show The Pajama Game. He will play the supervisor of a US pyjama factory. The musical will open in November, said the show's co-producer. It has a score by Richard Adler and Jerry Ross, and two new songs.

Number of British films produced in the UK fell 40% in 2004, says Screen Daily. UK and US co-productions in Britain fell from 102 in 2003 to 81 last year. Several projects were shelved as they faced the implications of the tax clampdown. The UK Film Council said it was too early to predict whether the trend would continue.

Film star Fox behind theatre bid in Swansea, Wales. £500,000 needed to buy Grade II listed building. Palace Theatre was sold to an undisclosed bidder at auction 13 months ago. Sir Anthony Hopkins made his professional debut there. Charlie Chaplin and Lily Langtry have also trodden its boards.

British stars Imelda Staunton and Clive Owen are hoping for awards. Hollywood stars Leonardo diCaprio, Pierce Brosnan, Christian Slater and Richard Gere are also in the audience for the biggest night in UK film. The Aviator leads the field with 14 nominations including best movie.

Judge rules Lee should get 10% of profits from Marvel TV and movie productions. Lee took legal action in 2002, saying Marvel shut him out of "jackpot" profits. Spider-Man and its sequel made $1.6bn (£857m) at box offices worldwide.

Britney Spears writes to US tabloids saying they are 'false' and 'desperate' The singer has been accused of lying about her marriage to Kevin Federline. In February, Us Weekly published pictures of her honeymoon without permission. The magazine said they were assured the pictures would only be used for a scrapbook.

Music mogul Fuller sells company to US entrepreneur Robert Sillerman. Mr Fuller has been appointed to the CFX board and will plan and implement the company's creative strategy. The 19 firm handles a roster of music artists, TV shows and PR strategies for stars including the Beckhams.

Elvis's number one is the 999th in chart history and comes the day after what would have been his 70th birthday. X Factor winner Steve Brookstein down into second place after three weeks in the charts. In at number three was Iron Maiden for the Number Of The Beast and Erasure entered the chart at four.

Oscars steer clear of controversial films. Michael Moore's Bush-baiting documentary Fahrenheit 9/11 overlooked. Mel Gibson's The Passion of the Christ receives nominations only in'minor' categories. But some potentially contentious pictures have won nominations. The Downfall, a biopic tracing the final days of Nazi leader Adolf Hitler.

The 1964 film shows the Doors frontman, who died aged 27 in 1971, playing the part of a young man who had been rejected by Florida State University. Morrison is seen quizzing a college administrator on why he was refused. "It's incredible. He's so clean cut and soft-spoken," said Florida state archivist Jody Norman.

Lopez misses UK charity premiere of her new movie Shall We Dance? She said: "I very much wanted to be in London but unfortunately I'm not well" Co-star Richard Gere attended the event held in aid of the tsunami appeal. Thousands braved the cold weather to see the stars in Leicester Square.

Aaliyah's record company has failed in an attempt to sue the video producer who booked the ill-fated flight on which she died in 2001. New York appeals court has told Blackground Records that only the singer's parents had the right to launch a claim for wrongful death.

Christina Applegate had to pull out of pre-Broadway performances with a broken foot. Producer Barry Weissler said he was "deeply proud" of the show. Sweet Charity tells the story of Charity Hope Valentine, a dancer who always falls in love with the wrong man.

Lee to create new film superhero with producer Robert Evans. Will focus on a character who has to face problems in everyday life. Lee is best known for his work on Spider-Man and The Incredible Hulk. Many of Lee's other creations, including X-Men and Daredevil, have been turned into films.

Singer Ian Brown 'in gig arrest' after fight at San Francisco gig. Spokesman says a fan jumped on stage and attacked the former Stone Roses singer. He then got into a fracas with a security guard, the spokesman said. Brown was arrested at his hotel after the show but released without charge.

Courtney Love must serve three years probation for assault and drug offences. She must also do 100 hours community service, have drug treatment, attend Narcotics Anonymous and pay a fine. Her lawyer Howard Weitzman said she had "turned her life around" and was "clean and sober"
