Eastwood's Baby scoops top Oscars for best picture and best director. Million Dollar Baby beat Martin Scorsese's The Aviator to the top awards. Jamie Foxx picked up best actor for playing soul star Ray Charles in Ray. Cate Blanchett won best supporting actress for her role as Katharine Hepburn.

Richey Edwards, guitarist and lyricist for The Manic Street Preachers, vanished 10 years ago, on 1 February 1995. His disappearance remains one of the most tragic mysteries in rock music. Edwards was the figurehead for their first, dangerous and dazzling incarnation. He battled depression, alcohol problems, eating disorders, and self-harm.

Super Size Me is a new series on CNN.com. The series follows the life of a man who eats nothing but food for a month. It is the first of its kind to be shown in the U.S. and has been shown around the world. For more information on the series, visit the website: www.supersizeme.org

Sizzla must serve 15 days in prison after he consistently swore during a concert in St Thomas, Jamaica. He was charged under a law which prohibits indecent dress or expression. His UK tour was cancelled last November after protests by gay rights campaigners. One of his most controversial songs, Pump Up, contains the Jamaican patois lyrics "fire fi di man dem weh go ride man behind"

Bangkok International Film Festival has continued as originally planned. Organisers have been careful to be respectful of the Thai nation's recovery. The eclectic programme contains a wide range of titles, including Oscar hopefuls. But the absence of Thai subtitles may have proved offputting to local cinemagoers.

The 77th annual Academy Awards are taking place on 27 February. But from humble beginnings, how did the modern day extravaganza become the behemoth it is today? There are now 5,700 members of the Academy - with membership by invitation only to those who are seen to have achieved distinction in the movies.

UK CD albums market grew by 4.5% in 2004 with a record 174.6 million units sold. On average every Briton buys 3.2 CDs per person per year. Around 26,000 albums are released in the UK each year, making Britain second only to the US in terms of the number of releases.

Sideways wins all six awards for which it was nominated. Alexander Payne wins best director and best screenplay. Best actress goes to Catalina Sandino Moreno for Maria Full of Grace. Scrubs star Zach Braff wins award for best first feature for Garden State. Last year's big winner, Lost In Translation, went on to win the Oscar.

Halloween writer Debra Hill dies in Los Angeles aged 54. She had been suffering from cancer. Hill co-wrote the 1978 film, which starred Jamie Lee Curtis as a babysitter. Directed by John Carpenter, it made over $60m worldwide - a record for independent film at that time.

Carson, who hosted the Tonight Show for 30 years, died on 23 January from respiratory disease emphysema. He lived in Norfolk, Nebraska from the age of eight until he joined the Navy. Carson donated $5m (£2.7m) to local causes, including $600,000 to Norfolk High School in the 1980s.

Row threatens Hendrix museum plan in Seattle. Supporters hoped to turn the home into a museum for the guitarist. City of Seattle wants its new plot to be used for development. The house was moved when the land it was built on was being developed for housing in 2002. It has now been given a deadline of 22 February.

Rowlands starred in nine of the popular Carry On films, alongside fellow regulars Sid James, Kenneth Williams and Barbara Windsor. She also carved out a successful television career, appearing for many years in ITV's Bless This House. Her last appearance on stage was as Mrs Pearce in the award-winning production of My Fair Lady at the National Theatre.

Animated movie Howl's Moving Castle took 20bn yen (£102m) to become biggest film in Japan in 2004. Japanese films accounted for 37.5% of Japan's box office total last year. The Last Samurai, starring Tom Cruise, was the biggest foreign movie hit.

Fry will provide the voice of The Guide, an electronic book which accompanies Arthur Dent on his travels around the galaxy. Martin Freeman, John Malkovich, Bill Nighy and Alan Rickman are co-starring in the film, due for release in May. The late Douglas Adams' original 1977 scripts have also been turned into a series of successful books.

BBC to pour £9m into new comedy and entertainment programmes outside London. Director of television Jana Bennett said the changes were about "getting the best ideas on screen as efficiently and effectively as we can" A number of new roles are being created in each department, including head of comedy commissioning based in Glasgow.

Singer says he wants to "move his career into a different form" A Different Story chronicles Michael's life and career from the 1980s and his personal struggles. The 41-year-old chart-topper said it would be a much more "behind the scenes affair" He hinted at discontent with the current state of the music industry.

Ray DVD beats box office takings with a combined tally of $80m (£43m) The film has been nominated in six Oscar categories including best film and best actor for Jamie Foxx. In its first week on home entertainment release the film was the number one selling DVD.

Tarantino has written an original story for the season finale episode. Co-producer said the episode would have "more bugs and blood" than usual. It is not Tarantino's first venture into TV. In 1995 he directed an episode of the medical drama ER.

Patti Smith to host arts festival at London's South Bank Centre in June. Follows Morrissey, David Bowie and Nick Cave in directing 15 days of concerts and events. Smith has yet to decide the line-up for Meltdown, which begins on 11 June, but wants to touch on all aspects of our culture.

Shark Tale DVD is US best-seller so far this year. It sold more than 6 million DVDs and videos across the United States and Canada. The all-time first-week record is held by 1995's Lion King followed by Shrek 2, Finding Nemo and Monster's Inc.

Smith's romantic comedy Hitch dropped to second place with takings of $21m (£10.9m) Keanu Reeves' supernatural thriller Constantine dropped a place to three. The low-budget feature Diary of a Mad Black Woman stars Kimberly Elise as a woman thrown out on the streets by her philandering husband.

Keanu Reeves awarded a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame. The 40-year-old is best known for his role in the Matrix movies. His star is the 2,277th to be embedded on Hollywood Boulevard. He thanked his mother, Patricia, for inspiring him to become an actor.

Joss Stone wins two awards: best British female act and best urban act out of three award nominations. Muse beat Franz Ferdinand, Jamie Cullum, Kasabian and The Libertines forBest British live act. Teenager also has Grammy nominations in the US, normally dominated by home-grown acts.

Pixies, Foo Fighters and Iron Maiden will play at Reading and Leeds. The Killers, Razorlight and Queens of the Stone Age will also play. It will be the first time the veteran British metal band have played in 23 years. Weekend tickets are now on sale priced at £125.

Elvis fans around the world have been marking the legendary singer's 70th birthday. A three-day Elvis convention took place in Blackpool, England, over the weekend. Graceland, Tennessee, was the focus for US celebrations with four days of events. Elvis' single Jailhouse Rock became the UK's number one on Sunday.

Double win for Sea Inside at Bangkok International Film Festival. Javier Bardem named best actor and Annette Bening best actress. Joel Schumacher wins lifetime achievement award. Hong Kong director Wong Kar-Wai honoured for promoting Asian cinema. The festival is donating profits from ticket sales to tsunami relief fund.

Musicians' groups call for an end to the "raw deal" faced by British performers. Musicians face tougher regulations than athletes and journalists. US acts are not faced with comparable expense and bureaucracy when visiting the UK for promotional purposes. Department for Media, Culture and Sport says it is working with US embassy and record industry.

Scissor Sisters win best group, best album and best newcomer awards. Robbie Williams' Angels named best song of the past 25 years. Joss Stone voted best urban act by digital TV viewers. Keane, Keane and McFly all win British breakthrough acts prizes. Bob Geldof wins outstanding contribution to music.

Original Exorcist to be screened at the International Festival of Fantastic Film in Brussels. The psychological drama stars Stellan Skarsgard and foreruns the 1973 film. It will be the first time that Paul Schrader's version of the film has been seen in public.

Briton Andrea Arnold wins short film Oscar for her film Wasp. Three of the five nominees in the live-actionShort film category were British. Arnold is currently working on a feature film with Dogville and Dancer In The Dark director Lars Von Trier. Her film has won 30 awards worldwide, including one at Sundance.

Critics back Aviator for Oscars. Several of those surveyed think the veteran film-maker will lose the best director prize to Clint Eastwood. Most of the critics tipped Jamie Foxx and Hilary Swank to scoop best actor and actress for Ray and Million Dollar Baby respectively.

French honour for director Parker. Sir Alan's films include Oscar-winning Fame plus Midnight Express and The Commitments. He praised French films, saying: "Hollywood, which created modern cinema, uses it only as a commodity" The Order of Arts and Letters is one of France's highest cultural honours.

Boogeyman took £788,439 in its first three days on release. Oscar nominee Hotel Rwanda was also a new entry in the chart. Clint Eastwood's Million Dollar Baby re-entered the charts at number eight. Two other new entries, Flight of the Phoenix and Harold and Kumar Get The Munchies, debuted outside the top 10.

Brits debate over 'urban' music. Joss Stone, a 17-year-old soul singer from Devon, beat Dizzee Rascal, Jamelia, Lemar and The Streets to win best British urban act at the Brit Awards. Her victory has reignited the debate about what urban music is.

Joss Stone has been nominated for Best Solo Female, Best Urban Act and Best Breakthrough Artist. Her second album Mind, Body & Soul reached number one in the UK charts last October. Ms Stone is due to perform at the 25th award ceremony at London's Earls Court.

Tautou will play Hanks' code-cracking partner, according to various newspapers. She is currently starring in A Very Long Engagement, directed by Jean-Pierre Jeunet. UK actress Kate Beckinsale had been widely tipped as a possibility for the role.

William Hill has stopped taking bets on who will be the next James Bond. The firm closed the book on Friday, saying "insider information" could have contributed to the number of bets. One punter had placed a bet of £870 on the 39-year-old actor at odds of 8-1.

New media battle for Bafta awards. BBC has 16 nominations while The Guardian has three. Awards recognise the best websites, digital TV shows and CD roms. The winners from 12 different categories are crowned on 2 March 2005. There were nearly 400 entries this year - a third more than last year.

Grammys honour soul star Charles who died in 2004. U2, Usher, Norah Jones and Kanye West got three each. Britney Spears picked up her first ever Grammy for her song Toxic. Rod Stewart won the first Grammy of his career for Stardust... The Great American Songbook.

Robots follows a robot inventor who moves to a big city. Will Smith comedy Hitch has become the top film at the global box office. Recut version of Mel Gibson's The Passion of the Christ took just $239,850 (£125,000), despite opening in 957 cinemas.

Stallone and John McCririck faced the public vote on Friday. 67% of people voted to keep the racing pundit in the house. Stallone said: "I'm a total wreck, I need a vacation, this was a nightmare" Bookmakers have made former Happy Mondays dancer Bez favourite to win the show.

No UK premiere for Lord of the Rings musical. £11.5m show will make its debut in Toronto in March 2006. All three West End theatres with sufficient capacity were booked. Up to five British actors may join the cast, under a deal struck with Canadian Actors' Equity.

William Hill made the move after four people tried to place bets on Friday's surprise double eviction. The bookmaker said its suspicions had been aroused by betting for the last two contestant evictions. A Big Brother spokeswoman was "satisfied" that sensitive information about the show remained confidential.

The Colombian-born actress was the final hope for director Joshua Marston. The 23-year-old play a teenage drug mule who smuggles heroin by swallowing pellets in condoms. Her previous acting experience was in amateur productions in her home city of Bogota at the Ruben Di Pietro theatre academy.

Farrell due to make US TV debut in medical sitcom Scrubs. He will make a cameo appearance as an unruly Irishman. The episode featuring the 28-year-old will be screened on 25 January. Farrell is pencilled in to play the role of Crockett in Miami Vice.

Saul Israel Holiff managed Johnny Cash between 1960 and 1973. The Canadian music manager also managed Tommy Hunter and the Statler Brothers. He had been in declining health, according to his family. There will be no funeral service for the 79-year-old, who died on 17 March.

Women in the UK film industry earn less than their male counterparts. Only 16% of women earn more than £50,000, compared with 30 per cent of men. Women are less likely than men to be married or have dependant children. The workforce is largely focused around London, with 78% based there.

Casino Royale will be the 21st James Bond film to hit the big screen. Goldeneye director Martin Campbell will direct the film. The script will once again be developed by Neal Purvis and Robert Wade. No decision has yet been made on who will become the seventh actor to play Bond.

Mel Brooks' hit show triumphed in the battle for best new musical. It was up against Mary Poppins and Andrew Lloyd Webber's The Woman in White. The History Boys was the big winner in straight theatre categories, picking up three trophies. Dame Judi Dench, who starred in All's Well That Ends Well, lost out in best supporting role category.

Hoffman said the film culture was "in the craphouse" at a press conference. The 67-year-old also said he stopped working a few years ago because he lost his "spark" for acting. Hoffman is in the UK to publicise his new comedy, Meet the Fockers.

Smith plays a New York "date doctor" with love worries of his own. It held off a strong challenge from the new Keanu Reeves sci-fi thriller Constantine. Two family films came next in the chart, with Wayne Wang's comedy Because of Winn-Dixie in third position.

Rapper 50 Cent has ended his public feud with his protege The Game. The pair said they wanted to be good role models for their communities. They shook hands as they handed over money to music projects for New York's deprived areas. A member of the Game's entourage was reportedly shot outside a radio station.

Hendrix guitar fetches £100,000 at an auction in London. The 1965 Fender Stratocaster was used by the musician on tour and in his studio. A poem written by Hendrix two weeks after his infamous appearance at the Monterey Festival where he set light to his guitar went for £10,00.

Stern dropped from radio stations in New York and Pennsylvania. Citadel said it did not yet know whether it would return to its network. The DJ's broadcasts are well known for landing in trouble with regulators for obscene and sexually explicit rantings. But Stern continues to be one of the most popular talk show hosts, particularly in the 25-54 age category.

Blue beat U2 to top France honour at the NRJ Music Awards. US band Maroon 5 was named best new international artist. Usher and Avril Lavigne won the international male and female prizes respectively. More than five million radio listeners voted in the awards.

Khan has had raunchy roles in music videos and Bollywood films over the past two years. Immigration officials said she had been warned about her visa last year. Khan was involved in controversy when topless photos alleged to be of her appeared in a Norwegian magazine.

Tarantino 'to make Friday sequel' according to the Hollywood Reporter. He will meet with New Line Cinema executives this week to discuss the project. The original film, released in 1980, has spawned ten sequels. Tarantino is currently filming the season finale of US television series CSI.

Corbett attacks 'dumbed-down TV' in Radio Times interview. He joins Victoria Wood and David Jason in bemoaning declining standards. Corbett is soon to reunite with Ronnie Barker for a new Two Ronnies series. The sitcom ran from 1971 to 1987 and attracted 17 million viewers at its peak.

Hollywood hunts hits at Sundance Film Festival. Stars like Keanu Reeves and Pierce Brosnan also have films showing there. The festival is being opened by a screening of quirky comedy Happy Endings, starring former Friends actress Lisa Kudrow and Maggie Gyllenhaal.

Buffy creator joins Wonder Woman movie. Joss Whedon described the DC Comics character as "the most iconic female heroine of our time" Linda Carter played the character in the 1970s TV series. The film is being produced by Joel Silver, producer of the Matrix trilogy.

Spears cancelled her Onyx Hotel tour last June after suffering a knee injury. She is seeking to be reimbursed for the tour's £5m ($9.3m) costs. Seven London-based companies and an eighth Paris firm have been given up to 30 days to respond to the complaint.

Babyshambles played for 5,000 fans at London's Brixton Academy on Tuesday. Singer Pete Doherty traded blows with guitarist Patrick Walden. They were separated and bundled off stage before returning to end the set. The show was earlier held up due to audience overcrowding.

Aviator and Vera take Bafta glory. Jamie Foxx wins best actor for Ray. British actor Clive Owen takes best supporting actor. Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban wins Orange Film Of The Year. The Motorcycle Diaries won best foreign film and best music. Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind took best original screenplay.

Housewives lift Channel 4 ratings. Celebrity Big Brother attracted less viewers than its 2002 series. BBC1 and ITV1 have both seen their monthly audience share decline. Digital multi-channel TV is continuing to be the strongest area of growth, with the BBC reporting Freeview box ownership of five million.

Portishead have revealed they are writing their third album. It will be their first album in eight years. The band will play a tsunami charity show next month. They will not play any new material at the event, which will feature singer Beth Gibbons playing with an acoustic backing.

Bollywood DVD fraudster is jailed for three years. Jayanti Amarishi Buhecha made £26,000 per month from his illegal trade. Fake DVDs were manufactured in Pakistan and Malaysia and sold on wholesale. Legitimate Bollywood film distributors have hailed the conviction as "a major boost"

Jackson film 'absolute disaster' says PR expert Ann Kite. She was hired to 'crisis manage' the fallout after the film aired in 2003. Jackson denies 10 charges of child abuse and false imprisonment. If convicted, he could face up to 21 years in prison.

Joy Division story to become film called Touching From A Distance. Music mogul Tony Wilson, who headed the record company Joy Division were signed to, will be co-executive producer. Curtis committed suicide in 1980 aged 23, shortly before the band were due to go on tour in the US.

Vera Drake, Mike Leigh's tale about a 1950s backstreet abortionist, is nominated in 11 categories. Empire magazine's reviews editor Dan Jolin said the film had "a very good chance" of doing well on Saturday. He predicted that it would collect five or six awards.

Bening, who was born in Texas in 1958, has gained prominence for a string of key roles. Although an Oscar has so far eluded her, her status as one of Hollywood's favourite actresses remains solid. She made her film debut as a sex-starved wife in 1988's The Great Outdoors.

Three boys will rotate the demanding role of ballet dancer Billy. The show's opening night on 12 May remains unaffected by the changes. Director Stephen Daldry: "This is one of the most ambitious projects I have been involved with" The three boys playing Billy are James Lomas, 15, George Maguire, 14 and Liam Mower, 12.

US 'afflicted' with awards fatigue according to some LA film critics. Bob Strauss from the LA Daily News calls awards shows a 'celebrity love-in' Entertainment Weekly's Dave Karger says the Oscars only generate excitement when a blockbuster is nominated. Screen International's Mike Goodridge thinks 2004's films have simply not grabbed the public's imagination.

Brits return Keane to number one with their album Hopes and Fears. U2's latest single Sometimes You Can't Make It On Your Own took the top spot in the singles chart. Elvis' Wooden Heart is the sixth in a series of 18 reissues to mark the 70th anniversary of Presley's birth.

It was the first time Dame Julie had seen the musical. She watched Laura Michelle Kelly, 23, reprise the role on stage. The show has been one of the West End's hottest tickets since opening in December. Kelly was named best musical actress at last month's Olivier Awards.

Fox's prime-time audience fell by 600,000 to 5.9 million last season. Chief executive Gail Berman said "in the case of this fall we drifted to too much on the unscripted side" She was predicting a drop in ratings even for some of the network's established reality shows, such as American Idol.

Elvis'set for chart hat-trick' with third UK number one in three weeks. A Fool Such As I, the next in a series of 18 reissues, is on course to beat the Chemical Brothers to the top. But his next single, It's Now Or Never, will face a challenge from tsunami charity single Grief Never Grows Old.

DJ double act revamp chart show on BBC Radio 1 on Sunday. JK and Joel will add showbiz news, celebrity interviews and between-song banter. Show has been overtaken in popularity by independent radio's Hit 40 UK rundown. The pair have worked together for a decade - meeting on Viking Radio in Hull.

Youssou N'Dour's album Egypt won the critics' award for album of the year. The best newcomer accolade went to Argentine Chango Spasiuk. Winners were chosen from ten categories to reflect different continents. A special Poll Winners concert will take place at The Sage in Gateshead on 5 March.

Singer earned $56.5m (£30.4m) from concerts, album and publishing sales. Madonna remained in second place because of the "monumental" production costs of her tour. Metallica's Madly in Anger with the World tour helped push their 2004 earnings up to £23.1m.

The British Phonographic Industry has identified a lack of independent music available for download. Downloaded singles have now overtaken physical singles in the UK. The BPI is running a series of seminars entitled Getting Your Music Online. In the US, download sales have already begun incorporating into the Billboard's Hot 100 chart.

Bookmakers back The Aviator for Oscar win. Jamie Foxx is clear favourite in best actor category. Million Dollar Baby's Hilary Swank is tipped to win the best actress prize. Cate Blanchett will be named best supporting actress. Clive Owen is second favourite to take a supporting actor award.

British stars denied major Oscars. UK's Andrea Arnold won the short film award for her gritty drama Wasp. British visual effects team behind Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban lost the Oscar in that category to Spider-Man 2. Mike Leigh's Vera Drake failed to take the director or screenplay awards and there was no prize for star Imelda Staunton.

De Niro film leads US box office with $22m (£11.7m) The actor recently spent three weeks at the top with comedy Meet The Fockers. Oscar hopefuls The Aviator, Million Dollar Baby and Sideways all cashed in.

This year marks Bill Conti's 17th turn at the helm of the Academy Awards orchestra. He received an Oscar in 1983 for the original score of The Right Stuff. The decision to drown out or 'kill' the offending star with music is relayed from the director's box to the orchestra via his earpiece.

Judy Craymer is the highest new entry in the Sunday Times' music rich list, with a £67m fortune. Former record label boss Clive Calder is top of the list with £1.3bn, up £40m on last year. Teenage soul singer Joss Stone, 17, is one of Britain's young music millionaires. The list also features Charlotte Church, Coldplay, Daniel Bedingfield and Will Young.

Kanye West rose to prominence by producing songs for Jay-Z and Alicia Keys. He then emerged from his behind-the-scenes role to become an artist as well as a producer. But his solo career almost ended before it began after a near-fatal car crash.

Black Sabbath top rock album poll with 1970 self-titled debut. Ozzy Osbourne appears more than any other act, with two solo records. Top five includes Led Zeppelin, Iron Maiden and Sex Pistols. Queen, Muse, Manic Street Preachers and The Clash complete the top 10.

Mick Mars is being sued by his ex-girlfriend for $10 million (£5.4 million) She claims he broke a promise to take care of her after they split in December. She is asking a Los Angeles court to award her half the musician's property, a monthly allowance and damages.

Stars shine on Bafta red carpet. Best actress winner Imelda Staunton says Vera Drake is highlight of her career. Martin Scorsese says being honoured in the UK means a lot to him. Younger stars of British film represented in shape of Emma Watson.

Oscar nominees lack pulling power according to box office figures. 51 million people in the US have seen this year's nominees, compared with between 100 million and 118 million in recent years. Last time combined attendance was so low was in 1984 when Amadeus beat The Killing Fields, A Passage to India, Places in The Heart and A Soldier's Story.

British actress Antonia Bernath is making her debut in Kisna - the Warrior Poet. The film marks a growing trend for non-Indian stars to appear in Bollywood films. Director Subhash Ghai's film is set in the British Raj and is shot in Hindi and English.

More than 45,000 people were surveyed by digital TV station Music Choice. Queen's Who Wants to Live Forever was highly favoured by both UK and European voters. Britons requested the Royal Scots Dragoon Guards' Amazing Grace and their continental counterparts opted for Mozart's Requiem.

Theo van Gogh's Submission pulled from Rotterdam Film Festival. Film is critical of the treatment of women under Islam. Its TV screening is thought to have led to his murder in 2004. Two of his other films will be shown as planned at the 10-day festival.

Arnold's film Wasp won the best live action short film award on Sunday. The film has already won over 30 other international awards including the Sundance Short Film Prize. Arnold, from Dartford in Kent, described her victory as "truly overwhelming" The director was one of only two British winners on the night.

T in the Park tickets sell out just four days after the line-up was announced. Green Day, the Foo Fighters and Keane are among the acts on the bill. More than 120 acts will play on eight stages over the weekend of 9 and 10 July. Last year tickets sold out 10 weeks before the festival but organisers confirmed all 130,000 for the two-day event had been sold.

Rap star 50 Cent says he has thrown protege The Game out of his G-Unit gang. A man was shot in the thigh outside New York's Hot 97 studios on Monday. More shots were fired outside his management offices two hours later. No arrests have been made in relation to either incident.

US composer recreates Bach score for Wedding Cantata BWV 216. The 1728 composition was found among the papers of Japanese pianist Chieko Hara. Work, written for the wedding of a German customs official, was missing for 80 years. Joshua Rifkin has recreated the missing instrumental parts.

Career honour for actor DiCaprio at Santa Barbara International Film Festival. Martin Scorsese, who directed him in Oscar-nominated movie The Aviator, presented the award. "It's a lifetime achievement award, which is completely and utterly surreal, given I'm only 30 years old," he said.

The original stage production of The Sound of Music is to be performed for the first time in the Austrian capital, 40 years after the film was released. The musical is based on the true story of the von Trapp family who formed a singing troupe and escaped from Nazi-occupied Austria in 1938. Despite being one of most successful musicals of all time, it is barely known inside Austria.

Huw Stephens, Ras Kwame and Rob Da Bank will each host the mid-week, late-night timeslot, showcasing UK talent. Radio 1 said the show would not try to replace Peel, but would rise to the "challenge" of "keeping his legacy alive" Peel died after suffering a heart attack in Peru in October.

Michelle Paver's Wolf Brother is the first in a planned series of six books. Film studio Fox has bought the rights for around $4m (£2.13m) for Scott's company Scott Free to develop. The director said he was "thrilled" with the project.

Mogul Wilson backing UK rap band Raw T. The group are set to release their first single on 21 February. They will follow it up with an album, Realise And Witness, in March. Wilson believes they could be "to F4 as Joy Division were to Factory records"

Franz Ferdinand's self-titled debut has sold more than 600,000 copies in 11 months. In September it was named album of the year winning the prestigious Mercury Music Prize. The four-piece met two years ago when drummer Paul Thomson was working at the Glasgow art school where bassist Bob Hardy was studying.

Abba reunite for musical premiere of Mamma Mia! in Stockholm. First public reunion since band's acrimonious break-up in the early 1980s. The musical, which has become a global phenomenon, will be performed in Swedish for the first time. More than 20 million people around the world have seen the show.

George Michael to perform for BBC Radio 2 special on 18 December. The session will also see him talk about how his biggest hits came about. Chris Tarrant will host a one-off New Year's Eve show on the station. Other Christmas specials include a spoof nostalgia show and a gospel concert.

Moya led Spain to victory over the USA but wants to focus on the Grand Slams in 2005. 1998 French Open champion is determined to make an impact in the major events after spending much of the last eight years in top 10. "At the age of 29 I have set some tough goals in my professional career," he says.

Serena Williams has moved up five places to second in the world rankings. Williams won her first Grand Slam title since 2003 with victory over Lindsay Davenport. Men's champion Marat Safin remains fourth in ATP rankings while beaten finalist Lleyton Hewitt replaces Andy Roddick as world number two.

Safin says he has "given up" on Wimbledon after losing in round one last year. The 25-year-old won his second Grand Slam title at the Australian Open. Safin lost to Lleyton Hewitt 6-1 in the final on Sunday.

Rochus shocks Coria in Auckland Open semi-final. Top seed loses 6-4 6 -4 to Belgium's Olivier Rochuus. R Cochuis will play Czech Jan Hernych in the final. Fifth seed Fernando Gonzalez beats Robby Ginepri. Heineken Open starts on Thursday.

World Cup winners Lawrence Dallaglio, Neil Back and Martin Johnson had all been thought to be in the frame for next summer's tour to New Zealand. Woodward: "I would have to have a compulsive reason to pick any player who is not available to international rugby"

Ireland's Brian O'Driscoll will lead the Northern Hemisphere team in the IRB Rugby Aid match at Twickenham. South will be led by George Gregan, one of four Wallabies, alongside five Springboks and four All Blacks including captain Tana Umaga. North side hit by withdrawals of Scotland duo Gordon Bulloch and Chris Cusiter, plus France captain Fabien Pelous.

Charvis has missed all three of Wales' victories with an ankle injury. Sonny Parker is continuing to struggle with a neck injury, but Hal Luscombe should be fit for the Murrayfield trip. Robin McBryde remains a doubt after picking up knee ligament damage in Paris last Saturday.

Rico Gear ran in two of the All Blacks' seven tries in what was a predominantly second-string line-up. Albert van den Bergh, Xavier Rush and Andrea Lo Cicero scored tries for the Baa-Baas. The match was blighted by controversy when Justin Marshall, was felled with a high tackle by Jimmy Cowan.

Bath have signed former Ospreys scrum-half Andy Williams on a short-term deal. Williams, whose contract with the Welsh region was due to expire in June, has agreed a contract until the end of the season. Bath need experienced back-up to Nick Walshe after Martyn Wood's injury.

Castaignede fires Laporte warning. Former France fly-half says pressure is mounting on coach. France suffered a shock loss against the Welsh at the weekend after looking on course for an easy win. The 30-year-old also tipped Yann Delaigue to start ahead of Frederic Michalak.

Ivan Ljubicic beats Tim Henman 7-5 6-4 in Dubai Open quarter-final. Rain interrupted the match seven times during the second set. Tommy Robredo beat Nicolas Kiefer of Germany to reach semi-finals.Henman: "It was incredibly frustrating. It's raining and the umpire doesn't take control"

Lindsay Davenport beats Nicole Vaidisova of the Czech Republic. Former world number one Venus Williams beats Anna Smashnova in straight sets. Australian 10th seed Victoria Dementieva beats Daniela Hantuchova. French Open champion Lucie Myskina beats Francesca Schiavone of Italy.

Minister Claude Eerdekens claims Svetlana Kuznetsova tested positive for ephedrine at an exhibition event last month. He said he made the statement in order to protect the other three players that took part in the tournament, Belgian Justine Henin-Hardenne, Nathalie Dechy of France and Russia's Elena Dementieva.

Wales number eight Michael Owen says replacing Gareth Thomas as Wales' captain will be straightforward because of the leadership quality in the squad. Coach Mike Ruddock says the 24-year-old should take the armband from broken thumb victim Thomas against Scotland. Owen admitted the Grand Slam had been mentioned within the Wales squad but that no-one was getting carried away with the three victories over England, Italy and France.

Roger Federer beats Juan Carlos Ferrero in three sets at the Dubai Open. World number one saves two match points in tiebreak to reach quarter-finals. Swiss star will face Russian Mikhail Youzhny in the last eight in Dubai. Click here for all the latest tennis news.

Vickery fractured the radius in his right forearm during Gloucester's 17-16 win over Bath on Saturday. He will undergo an operation on Monday and is expected to be out for at least six weeks. Vickery spoke with Bath prop David Barnes, who also broke his arm recently.

Wales silent on Grand Slam talk despite third Six Nations win. Captain Gareth Thomas ruled out of rest of campaign with a broken thumb. Robin McBryde is doubtful after picking up a knee injury in Paris. Scotland secured their first win of the campaign on Saturday by grinding out an 18-10 win over Italy.

Wales coach Mike Ruddock has defended his decision not to release any of the international stars for this weekend's regional Celtic League fixtures. The Ospreys and Scarlets say they are happy to support the Wales cause, but the Dragons have expressed disappointment at not being able to use their national squad players.

Former England captain Lawrence Dallaglio still harbours hopes of a place on the British and Irish Lions tour to New Zealand. Lions coach Sir Clive Woodward has made it clear he will pick his squad to tour next summer based on form shown in the Six Nations championship. "I know what it takes and what I have to offer," he told the Daily Telegraph.

Wales captain Gareth Thomas ruled out of rest of Six Nations with broken thumb. Full-back will have surgery on Monday after fracturing his thumb in 24-18 win over France on Saturday. Phil Bennett insists Wales can cope without Thomas as they chase a first Grand Slam in 27 years.

Svetlana Kuznetsova has tested positive for a banned drug, according to Belgian authorities. The Russian world number five was playing in an exhibition event in Charleroi at the time. Belgian sports minister Claude Eerdekens said that the stimulant ephedrine was discovered.

Tim Henman faces Cyril Saulnier in the first round of next week's Australian Open. British number two Greg Rusedski could face Andy Roddick if he beats Jonas Bjorkman. Defending champion Roger Federer faces Fabrice Santoro. Women's top seed Lindsay Davenport drew Spanish veteran Conchita Martinez.

Tottenham drew 0-0 with Manchester United in the Premier League on Sunday. The game was marred by a goal that was clearly over the line. But the referee did not see it until after the game had finished. Arsene Wenger has called for the use of video replays in football.

Wales hooker Mefin Davies is likely to stay with English side Gloucester. Davies was one of the stars of Saturday's Six Nations win over England. The 32-year-old is only on a year contract at Kingsholm. BBC Wales understands the Ospreys are interested in the former Celtic Warriors player.

Vickery was injured as Gloucester beat Bath 17-16 in the West country derby. He could be joined on the sidelines by Bath centre Olly Barkley, who sat out the derby due to a leg injury. Barkley will have a scan on Sunday and might miss England's trip to Six Nations leaders Ireland next weekend.

Slovakia will play Argentina in the final of the Hopman Cup after beating the Netherlands 3-0. Daniela Hantuchova defeated Michaella Krajicek to give the Slovaks the perfect start. Argentina claimed top spot in Group A with three wins from three matches. The United States defeated Australia 2-1 in other Group B match.

Second seed Andre Agassi beaten in straight sets by Jurgen Melzer in San Jose. Defending champion Andy Roddick rallies to beat Thomas Enqvist in quarter-finals. Cyril Saulnier and Tommy Haas also through to the last eight of the SAP Open.

Martina Navratilova will play doubles and mixed doubles events in 2005. The 48-year-old made a comeback after retiring in 1994. She will partner Nathalie Dechy in the doubles event at the Uncle Toby's Hardcourts tournament on Australia's Gold Coast.

Number eight Imanol Harinordoquy has been dropped from France's squad for the Six Nations match with Ireland in Dublin on 12 March. Bourgoin lock Pascal Pape, who has recovered from a sprained ankle, returns to the 22-man squad. Wing Cedric Heymans and Ludovic Valbon come in for Aurelien Rougerie and Jean-Philippe Grandclaude.

Stevens named in England line-up for Six Nations match against Ireland. It will be Stevens' first start after two caps as a replacement against the All Blacks last year. Leicester duo Ollie Smith and Andy Goode have been drafted onto the bench. England confirmed that Sale Sharks prop Andrew Sheridan was not considered for selection because of an injury.

Brian O'Driscoll sets up tries for Geordan Murphy and Peter Stringer. Denis Hickie also scores a converted try for Ireland. Italy lead 9-8 early in the second half but Ireland never lost the lead. Martin Castrogiovanni powered over for the hosts.

Slovakia beat Argentina 3-0 in the Hopman Cup final in Perth. Third seeds Daniela Hantuchova and Dominik Hrbaty win the singles and mixed doubles. The win makes up for last year's final defeat to the United States.

Tindall aiming to earn Lions spot by 18 April. The World Cup winner has been out of action since December. Brian O'Driscoll, Gordon D'Arcy and Gavin Henson will all be in contention for a place on the tour to New Zealand.

O'Driscoll was originally named in the starting line-up but has failed to recover from the hamstring injury he picked up against Italy. His replacement will be named after training on Friday morning. Fellow centre Gordon D'Arcy is also struggling with a hamstring and will undergo a fitness test.

Roger Federer has won 11 titles from 11 finals during 2004 - three of them Grand Slams. The number one player in the world is also the main man for promoting the sport off court. He has just been voted, by the International Tennis Writers, the best "Ambassador for Tennis" on the ATP Tour.

Sydney will host a northern versus southern hemisphere charity match in June or July. Match will include players from the Lions tour of New Zealand. The date is yet to be decided but the most likely venue is Sydney's Olympic Stadium. Wallabies captain George Gregan says the match is a "great initiative"

Lleyton Hewitt beaten by Taylor Dent in quarter-finals of Australian Hardcourt Championships. The top seed was a strong favourite for the title but went down 7-6 (7-4) 6-3 to the American. Dent will face Juan Ignacio Chela next after he beat Jurgen Melzer. Olivier Rochus beat third seed Nicolas Kiefer and will take on Joachim Johansson.

Lewis Moody, Geordan Murphy and Martin Corry scored tries for Leicester. Wasps fought back through Josh Lewsey try and Mark van Gisbergen's boot. Fly-half Andy Goode kicked 22 points in total for the Tigers. Leicester's domination in the scrums ultimately told.

Fifth seed Carlos Moya loses to fellow Spaniard Guillermo Garcia-Lopez. Four-time champion Andre Agassi beats German qualifier Dieter Kindlmann. Gael Monfils uses wild card to beat American Robby Ginepri. French Open champion Gaston Gaudio beats Justin Gimelstob.

Andy Roddick will play Cyril Saulnier in the final of the SAP Open in San Jose. The American top seed beat Germany's Tommy Haas 7-6 (7-3) 6- 3. SaulNier survived an injury scare in his semi-final with seventh-seeded Austrian Jurgen Melzer.

Kirwan demands Italy consistency in Six Nations. Italy lost 28-17 to Ireland in their opening game of the tournament. They face Wales on Saturday in the next round of matches. Kirwan was pleased with the performance of Alessandro Troncon and Luciano Orquera, despite the fly-half having an off-day.

Andrew Murray will become Britain's youngest-ever Davis Cup player. The 17-year-old will eclipse the record set by Roger Becker back in 1952. Greg Rusedski takes Tim Henman's place as first choice in the singles, while Alex Bogdanovic will play in second singles clash.

Former France centre Philippe Sella believes coach Bernard Laporte must recall Frederic Michalak to give his side any chance of beating Ireland. The 22-year-old has spent much of the tournament on the bench after Delaigue impressed for Castres early in the season.

Healey has been in good form in the Tigers' resurgence this season. The 31-year-old has reverted to the wing, where he won most of his England caps. Leicester face Wasps in their return Heineken Cup clash on Sunday. Healey hopes to use the match as a further springboard to an England recall.

England face Ireland at Lansdowne Road in Dublin on Sunday. Ireland are going for their first Grand Slam since 1948. England have lost eight of their last 13 matches since the World Cup final. Brian O'Driscoll will return for Ireland after missing the Scotland game.

Williams says he will never quit as Scotland coach. Scotland have lost 12 of their 14 games under his leadership. Williams has yet to experience an RBS Six Nations victory after seven attempts. He rejected the comparison made in some media sources with Berti Vogts, recently sacked asScotland football manager.

England centre Mike Tindall is to seek a second opinion before having surgery on a foot injury. Bath player was already out of the opener against Wales on 5 February because of a hand problem. England coach Andy Robinson is already without centre Will Greenwood and flanker Richard Hill while fly-half Jonny Wilkinson is certain to miss at least the first two games.

Campese berates whingeing England after their defeat to Ireland. Former Australian wing insists England are "no longer world class" But Campese defends coach Andy Robinson, who he believes was the "only choice" after Sir Clive Woodward's resignation. England face a potential wooden spoon match against Italy on 12 March.

Ronan O'Gara's first-half try helped the Irish to a 8-3 lead at half-time. Percy Montgomery penalties set up a frantic finish but Ireland held out to claim a famous victory. It was only Ireland's second ever win over South Africa.

Venus Williams beaten by Sylvia Farina Elia in first round of Dubai Championships. Former Wimbledon champion Conchita Martinez and India's Sania Mirza also reach second round. US Open champion Svetlana Kuznetsova will now face Miraza.

Tigers wary of Farrell 'gamble' if he decides to switch codes. Leicester and Saracens are believed to head the list of rugby union clubs interested in signing the Great Britain rugby league captain. "Whoever does take him on is going to take a big, big gamble," says Tigers boss John Wells.

Corry backs skipper Robinson to lead England back to winning ways. England face Ireland at Lansdowne Road this weekend. Ireland are the form team of the tournament and are tipped to claim their first Grand Slam since 1948. Corry insists England are in the right frame of mind for the contest.

Wenger shock at Newcastle dip into the bottom half of the table. Gunners travel to St James' Park on Wednesday. Wenger says he is at a loss to explain Newcastle's poor form. Arsenal go into game on the back of a 2-0 victory over Fulham on Sunday.

Capriati is a two-time champion in Melbourne with wins in 2001 and 2002. Justin Henin-Hardenne and Kim Clijsters will also be absent from the women's draw. The first grand slam of 2005 begins on 17 January. It comes as a blow to last year's champion and runner-up.

Wales coach Mike Ruddock has made two changes from the team that beat Italy 38-8 for Saturday's trip to France. Kevin Morgan takes over from his injured Newport-Gwent Dragons colleague Hal Luscombe on the right wing. Ryan Jones is preferred at blindside flanker to Jonathan Thomas.

Johnny O'Connor will make his Ireland Six Nations debut against Scotland. The Wasps flanker replaces Denis Leamy in the starting line-up. He will be pushing hard for a recall for the following game against England. "There's a lot of competition here and I can't just drag my heels around if I don't get picked," he said.

Soderling wins tense Milan final against Radek Stepanek. The 20-year-old Swede edged the final set tie-break for a 6-36-7. 7-6 (7-5) victory. It is his second tour title after winning in Lyon last year.

Borders flanker has a knee injury and joins Donnie Macfadyen and Allister Hogg on the sidelines. Simon Taylor will miss at least the first two games after damaging an ankle during his comeback. Scott MacLeod (ankle ligaments) and Jon Petrie (cartilage) are also doubtful for the opener in Paris on 5 February.

Dawson missed Wasps' 12-9 loss to Bath on Saturday after injuring his right calf. Gloucester's Andy Hazell and Leicester star Lewis Moody also received knocks during their respective league matches. Jamie Noon is another player on the sidelines after he limped off in the first half against Saracens on Friday with a dead leg.

Bath faced with Tindall ultimatum over contract offer. Agent Dipo Alli says he has received an offer which dwarfs Bath's deal. Two other clubs want to talk to the 26-year-old England star. TIndall is out of contract at the end of the season.

Imanol Harinordoquy has been dropped from France's squad for the Six Nations match with Ireland in Dublin on 12 March. Bourgoin lock Pascal Pape, who has recovered from a sprained ankle, returns to the 22-man squad. Wing Cedric Heymans and Ludovic Valbon come in for Aurelien Rougerie and Jean-Philippe Grandclaude.

Capriati is a two-time champion in Melbourne with wins in 2001 and 2002. She is believed to have picked up the injury at the Advanta Championships at Philadelphia in November. Last year's champion Justin Henin-Hardenne and runner-up, Kim Clijsters, will also be absent.

England drawn against Samoa, France, Italy, Georgia and Chinese Taipei. Scotland and Ireland are in Pool A together with the All Blacks. England won the first event of the International Rugby Board World Sevens series in Dubai but have slipped to fourth in the table after failing to build on that victory.

France beat Scotland 16-9 in the opening match of the Six Nations. Bernard Laporte believes his team will be scared going into their game with England on Sunday. The French coach will announce his starting line-up on Wednesday. Perpignan centre Jean-Philippe Granclaude is delighted to have received his first call up to the France squad.

Philippoussis doubt over Open bid after suffering groin injury. 28-year-old suffered two tears to the adductor muscle. Hopman Cup doctor Hamish Osborne says he is unlikely to be fit in time. Former world number two Tommy Haas also a doubt for the Australian Open.

Lleyton Hewitt beats Andy Roddick in four sets to reach Australian Open final. The Australian will face Marat Safin in Sunday's final in Melbourne. He is aiming to be the first Australian winner since Mark Edmondson in 1976. "I've done a lot of hard yards to get here. Now I've got my chance," he said.

Jurgen Melzer beats second seed Andre Agassi in San Jose. Defending champion Andy Roddick rallies to beat Thomas Enqvist. Cyril Saulnier and Tommy Haas also through to quarter-finals of the SAP Open. The final will be played on Sunday.

Sania Mirza beats US Open champion Svetlana Kuznetsova at Dubai Championships. The 18-year-old Indian wins 6-46-2 in front of a delirious crowd. Daniela Hantuchova beats Alicia Molik in straight sets. Slovakian will meet Elena Likhovtseva in the second round.

Wales fly-half Stephen Jones happy to hand Gavin Henson responsibility for taking the match-winning kick against England. Jones had missed three earlier shots at goal when Wales, 9-8 down, were awarded a long-range penalty with four minutes left. Victory over England for the first time since 1999 will fuel expectations of what Wales might achieve in this year's Six Nations.

Sale Sharks director of rugby Philippe Saint-Andre has re-opened rugby's club-versus-country debate. Sale host Bath in the Powergen Cup on Friday, but the Frenchman has endured a "difficult week" with six players away on England's Six Nations training camp.

Wales hope openside flanker Martyn Williams will be fit for Saturday's RBS 6 Nations championship opener against England. Williams was expected to miss the match with a disc problem in his neck. Coach Mike Ruddock will name his starting line-up for the England game at 1830 GMT on Tuesday evening.

Ref stands by Scotland decisions after criticism by Matt Williams. Scotland coach said his side were robbed of victory by poor decisions made by the officials. Nigel Williams said: "I'm satisfied the game was handled correctly" Williams will not be punished by Scottish Rugby Union for allegedly using bad language in his comments.

Wilkinson return 'unlikely' with only two games left to play. Wilkinson is recovering from a knee injury which followed long-term neck and arm injuries. He has not played for England since the World Cup final in November 2003, since when the stuttering world champions have lost nine of their 14 matches.

Elena Dementieva beats defending champion Venus Williams in Hong Kong. Russian breaks Williams three times in the first set, while losing her service once. Williams saved three championship points before losing the match at the Victoria Park tennis court. Organizers auctioned off rackets belonging to the players, raising £115,000 for victims of the tsunami disaster.

Northampton coach Budge Pountney has been fined £2,000 and banned from match-day coaching for six weeks for calling a referee "a disgrace" The last two weeks of the six-week ban are suspended. The former Scotland international cannot enter the playing enclosure, technical areas or go near the touchline, tunnel or players and officials' areas.

Robinson answers critics about England's decline. England face France at Twickenham on Sunday in the Six Nations. Full-back Robinson believes the new-look team can stop the rot against France. Robinson also had words of comfort for 18-year-old Newcastle centre Mathew Tait.

England beat Fiji 26-21 in a dramatic final in Dubai to win the first IRB Sevens event of the season. Scotland were beaten 33-15 by Samoa in the plate semi-final and Ireland lost 17-5 to Tunisia. Portugal confirmed their impressive progress in sevens rugby by recording a sudden-death win over France.

Rugby union has become far more physically demanding since the game went professional nearly 10 years ago. The Professional Rugby Players' Association, the Rugby Football Union and Premier Rugby have launched an "injury audit" to find out how players are coping. "I think everybody in the English game has got to look at this. If we don't, it's going to get worse and not better," says Robinson.

Rafael Nadal beat Guillermo Canas 7-5 6-3 to reach the Mexican Open semi-finals. The eighth seed will play wild card Mariano Puerta in Acapulco. Czech fifth seed Jiri Novak was knocked out by Argentina's Agustin Calleri.

Donald Young beaten in straight sets by fellow American Robby Ginepri. Young shot to the top of the junior world rankings when he won the Australian Open. Top seed Andy Roddick launches his title defence against Paul Goldstein. Second seed Andre Agassi opens his campaign against Bobby Reynolds.

England coach Andy Robinson is facing disciplinary action after criticising referee Jonathan Kaplan in his side's Six Nations defeat to Ireland. The Rugby Football Union (RFU) will investigate Robinson after deciding not to lodge a complaint against Kaplan. Robinson may even have to apologise for his comments in order to avoid sanction from the International Rugby Board.

Hong Kong hoping to join Japan as co-host of the 2011 Rugby World Cup. Japan has applied to host the tournament on its own, with the aim of taking it outside rugby's traditional strongholds for the first time. The Japanese Rugby Football Union (JRFU) says it has yet to receive a formal presentation from the HKRFU.

Top-seeded Americans Andy Roddick and Andre Agassi survive minor scares to reach the last eight of the SAP Open in San Jose, California. Agassis endured early problems against left-handed Dane Kenneth Carlsen before sealing a 7-5 6-1 victory. And world number three R Oddick dropped a set to Korean player Hyung-Taik Lee, before pulling out a6-3 3-6 6 -2 win. Frenchman Cyril Saulnier, meanwhile, fired 19 aces to secure a win over Czech qualifier Tomas Zib.

Newcastle centre Mathew Tait scored one try and made another. The Falcons were 22-6 down at the break before a last-gasp try from Luke Narraway pulled the visitors level. Gloucester missed out on victory when Henry Paul fluffed the conversion and Seti Kiole was denied a try.

WRU proposes season overhaul. Celtic League in October, followed by the Heineken Cup in February and March, and the Six Nations moved to April and May. After a nine week break, the WRU then proposes a two-month period of away and home international matches.

Top seed Roger Federer wins 6-3, 7-6 (7-4) against world No. 2 Stanislas Wawrinka. The match was a repeat of last year's Wimbledon final, won by the Swiss in straight sets. It was the second time in two weeks that Federers had beaten the world number one.

Hodgkinson has been out injured for the last two years. He is set to leave the club at the end of the current season. "It's a good time for me to retire," he says. 'I'm looking forward to the next phase of my career'

Dominici backs lacklustre France to win the Six Nations Grand Slam. The champions only just saw off the Scots in Paris, then needed England to self-destruct in last week's 18-17 win. France take on Wales at the Stade de France on 26 February and Ireland in Dublin on 12 March.

Amelie Mauresmo beats Vera Zvonareva in straight sets. Maria Sharapova beats Svetlana Kuznetsova. Serena Williams beats Elena Dementieva for her second win in two days. The top two from each group will advance to the semi-finals.

Tim Henman named player of the year by the Lawn Tennis Association. The Briton reached the semis at the French and US Opens in 2004. Andrew Murray was named young player after winning the US Open juniors. Great Britain's under 14 boys won the team prize for their victory at World Junior Tennis.

Scotland beat Italy 18-10 in a dour but clinical encounter at Murrayfield. Six Chris Paterson penalties gave Scotland victory against Italy. Andrea Masi try was small consolation for Italy, chasing their first away win in the Six Nations. Coach Matt Williams' side were outmuscled and outplayed by the Azzurri pack.

France face England at Twickenham on Sunday. Wasps flanker Serge Betsen missed the victory over Scotland through injury. The player must attend a disciplinary hearing on Wednesday. Nicolas Mas, Jimmy Marlu and Jean-Philippe Grandclaude also included in a 22-man squad.

O'Driscoll saves Irish blushes with tries for Geordan Murphy and Peter Stringer. Italy cut the gap to 18-12 with 10 minutes left but Denis Hickie's try ensured an Irish victory. Ireland captain limped off late on, joining centre partner Gordon D'Arcy.

Roddick ended his 18-month partnership with Brad Gilbert on Monday. US Davis Cup assistant Dean Goldfine admits talks have taken place. "We're on the same page in terms of what I expect from a player in commitment and what he wants," says Gold fine.

Woodward eyes Brennan for Lions tour squad. Brennan last played for Ireland against Samoa in 2001. The 31-year-old former Dublin milkman moved from Leinster to Toulouse in 2003. Woodward is ensuring his preparations for the trip to New Zealand in June are as thorough as possible.

Robinson wants dual code success over Australia on Saturday. Rugby union captain leads England against Australia at Twickenham. Great Britain's rugby league team take on Australia in the final of the Tri-Nations tournament. Robinson: "Beating the Aussies in both games would be a massive achievement"

Wilkinson has not played since injuring his bicep on 17 October. He missed England's autumn internationals after aggravating the haematoma in his upper right arm against Saracens. The 25-year-old fly-half will start Saturday's Heineken Cup match at Murrayfield on the bench.

Ireland face USA at Lansdowne Road on Saturday 20 November. Tommy Bowe and Denis Leamy make their international debuts. David Humphreys, Kevin Maggs and Guy Easterby are all recalled. The States lost 39-31 against France in their last international and are ranked 16th.

Marat Safin beaten 7-6 (7-2) 6-4 by Nicolas Kiefer. Feliciano Lopez beats Paradorn Srichaphan to set up clash with Andre Agassi. Former champion Fabrice Santoro beaten by sixth seed Nikolay Davydenko.

Wales coach Mike Ruddock says England lock Danny Grewcock needs to review his actions after he kicked Dwayne Peel. Trouble flared at a ruck in the first half of Wales' 11-9 win in Cardiff. G Drewcock was sin-binned with Wales captain Gareth Thomas for retaliation.

Lewis Moody has flown to Dublin to join England's Six Nations camp. The Leicester flanker only has a "slim" chance of playing because of an infection in his finger. A decision will be taken on Saturday as to whether the 26-year-old is fit.

England lost 11-9 to Wales in the Six Nations opener on Saturday. Coach Andy Robinson is likely to make changes to his side for Sunday's clash with France. Lewis Moody and Martin Corry could both return after missing the game with hamstring and shoulder problems. The midfield pairing of Mathew Tait and Jamie Noon is also under threat.

White prepared for battle with Wales. The 31-year-old has made a massive contribution to the England and Leicester cause of late. He destroyed South Africa's Os du Randt in the scrum at Twickenham last autumn. White missed the vast majority of last year's Six Nations because of a knee injury.

Roger Federer became the first man since Mats Wilander in 1988 to win three Grand Slams in one season. Briton Tim Henman enjoyed his best year, while Greg Rusedski fought back superbly from adversity. The Russian women finally delivered on their long-recognised promise in 2004, with Anastasia Myskina, Maria Sharapova and Svetlana Kuznetsova winning Grand slams.

The Australian Open starts in Melbourne on January 14. The tournament is the first since the 2004 edition, which was won by Stanislas Wawrinka. It was the second time in three years that the tournament had been held in Australia. This year's tournament will be held at Melbourne Park, the home of the Open.

Dal Maso in to replace Bergamasco at flanker. Cristian Stoica is recalled at centre at the expense of Walter Pozzebon. Alessandro Troncon continues at scrum-half despite the return to fitness of Paul Griffen. "We are going to Scotland for the first away win and nothing else," said manager Marco Bollesan.

Williams stays on despite dispute over Scottish rugby's future direction. Chairman, chief executive and three non-executive directors all departed in a row. Williams: "I've brought my family here and we've immersed ourselves in Scottish life. There's no way that I'm walking away"

Munster's Heineken Cup quarter-final against Biarritz moved to Spain. The match will be played at Real Sociedad's Paseo de Anoeta stadium. Real's ground holds 32,000 whereas the Parc des Sports Aguilera has a capacity of just 12,667.

John Yapp is the only uncapped player in Wales' Six Nations squad. Wales coach Mike Ruddock backs the 21-year-old Blues prop's credentials. Ruddocks hopes the selection ofYapp and Dragons lock Ian Gough will send a message to other players in the country.

Tim Henman's decision to quit Davis Cup tennis has left the British team with a gargantuan void to fill. Captain Jeremy Bates has singled out Alex Bogdanovic and Andrew Murray as potential replacements. The 17-year-old Murray, with four Futures titles under his belt, looks the best long-term bet.

Tries from Jonathan Thomas, Tom Shanklin and Martyn Williams gave the visitors a 19-5 half-time advantage. Luciano Orquera did reply with one for Italy but second-half efforts from Brent Cockbain, Shane Williams and Robert Sidoli sealed victory.

Sir Clive Woodward will coach the Northern team against Rod Macqueen's Southern Hemisphere team in a tsumani fund-raising match at Twickenham. It will be a chance for Woodward to assess some of his options before unveiling his British and Irish Lions touring party, who will visit New Zealand in the summer.

Sania Mirza was the first Indian woman to reach the third round of a Grand Slam tennis event. The 18-year-old lost to women's favourite Serena Williams in Melbourne. Williams took just 56 minutes to win the match 1-6,4,6.

Wales beat France 18-15 in the Six Nations in Paris on Saturday. Wales have not won a Grand Slam since 1978. Mervyn Davies hails it as "one of the great performances of past three decades" Wales face Scotland at Murrayfield in their next match.

Scotland face Italy at Murrayfield in the Six Nations on Saturday. Italy have lost both their opening games at home to Ireland and Wales. Scotland coach Matt Williams is seeking a first victory at the eighth attempt. John Kirwan has warned his side they must eradicate the errors that blighted their loss to Wales or risk a third successive defeat.

Murphy: That was a bruising battle. We knew all along that we would be a huge threat particularly the first game in the Championship. It was not like the days gone by when you could get scores on the board early. Now we have to focus on Scotland and only six days to recover.

Lleyton Hewitt beats David Nalbandian in five sets to reach Australian Open semi-finals. The Australian third seed will play Andy Roddick in the last four. He looked to be cruising to victory after racing into a two-set lead. But the Argentine broke his serve three times in both of the next two sets.

Parmar picked up the injury last week and has failed to recover in time. Bogdanovic looks set to take the second singles place alongside Greg Rusedski. GB captain Jeremy Bates could use 17-year-old Andrew Murray and David Sherwood in the doubles rubber.

Fourth seed Safin survives injury scare to beat Mario Ancic. Top seed Federer through after opponent Jarkko Nieminen retires with injury. French Open champion Hrbaty out of tournament after five-set defeat. Agassi struggles past Dent but wins tie-break to reach fourth round.

Fuming Robinson blasts officials after 19-13 Six Nations loss to Ireland. Mark Cueto's first-half effort was ruled out for offside. Referee spurned TV replays when England crashed over in the dying minutes. England have lost four out of their six games since Robinson took over from Sir Clive Woodward in September.

Veteran Martinez wins Thai title for first time since Berlin in 2000. The 32-year-old Spaniard beats Anna-Lena Groenefeld in the final. Martinez is playing her last season on the Tour after a disappointing 2013. "To come through like that in an important match feels good," says Martinez.

Mirza makes Indian tennis history by winning the Hyderabad Open. The 18-year-old beat Alyona Bondarenko of the Ukraine 6-4 5-76-3. She is the first Indian in history to win a WTA singles title. Mirza sunk to her knees in celebration after serving out the match.

Serena Williams has angrily rejected claims that she and sister Venus are a declining force in tennis. Serena is through to the Australian Open semi-finals. Venus went out in the fourth round, meaning she has not gone further than the last eight in her last five Grand Slam appearances.

Wilkinson to miss Ireland match, according to Newcastle Falcons boss Rob Andrew. England have lost three Six Nations games in a row. Wilkinson has not played for England since the 2003 World Cup final. Former England full-back Dusty Hare puts England's mistakes down to a lack of mental toughness.

Davenport puts retirement on hold after having a largely injury-free 2004 campaign. The 28-year-old world number one had said that she would quit at the end of last year. She was due to take part in this week's Hopman Cup in Perth but decided to rest her knee.

Wales Students rugby side has become a casualty of the Welsh Rugby Union's reorganisation at youth level. An amalgamated Under-18 side formed from separate schools and national youth teams plays its first match on Thursday, against Italy at the Gnoll. The WRU decide to end its funding of representative sides such as Wales Students.

Davenport hits out at Wimbledon over equal prize money for women. World number one criticises All England Club chairman Tim Phillips. Club denies Phillips made the remark, insisting: "He definitely didn't say it" Dubai Duty Free event will join US and Australian Opens in offering women equal money.

South Africa's Schalk Burger named player of the year. Jake White claimed the coaching award. England player Simon Amor beat team-mate Ben Gollings and Argentine Lucio Lopez Fleming to win the sevens award for his performance in the World Sevens Series.

Nadal puts Spain 2-0 up in the tie. Roddick holds serve to force Nadal to serve for the match but the American surely cannot turn things around now. The game passes the two-hour mark as NadAl holds ahead to edge ahead. Carlos Moya beat Mardy Fish in straight sets to give Spain the lead.

There are four, five or probably six sides all competing at the same level. "Clearly, there is no number one side in the world," declared Wallabies on arrival back in Sydney. While that bodes well for rugby as a whole, it also sharpens the sense of excitement ahead of what could be the most open Six Championship for a decade.

Coach Andy Robinson dropped Matt Dawson for the autumn Tests after he missed training to film 'A Question of Sport' Newcastle's 18-year-old centre Mathew Tait is also in the training squad. The players in Robinson's elite squad can only play 32 matches for club and country. They can be called up for a total of 16 training days in addition to the recognised international weeks.

Officials respond in court row after criticism by Lleyton Hewitt. Tennis Australia's Geoff Pollard says surface is faster than last year. But he refuses to accept that surface may have had a bearing on his performances. The Australian Open starts on 17 January at Melbourne Park.

Ronan O'Gara kicked all of Ireland's points, with two dropped goals and five penalties, to give the home side a 100% record in their autumn internationals. The Pumas shocked the Irish early on with a try from Federico Aramburu, and Felipe Contepomi kicked 14 points.

Lleyton Hewitt beats Ivo Minar 7-5 6-0 in the final of the Sydney International. The Australian world number three has now won the title four times in six years. He is set to meet Frenchman Arnaud Clement in first round of Australian Open. Alicia Molik takes on Samantha Stosur in an all-Australian women's final later on Saturday.

Gavin Henson has staked the biggest claim for a place in the starting XV. Stephen Jones was another player who impressed me. Julian White is a capable player but Gethin Jenkins is now going to have the upper hand because he came out on top against Italy. Despite being written off beforehand several Scots caught my eye against France.

Tom Shanklin will start in the centre for Wales against England. Sonny Parker failed to recover from a trapped neck nerve. Mefin Davies plays at hooker, Martyn Williams is fit to start and Rob Sidoli replaces veteran Gareth Llewellyn. Robin McBryde sits on the bench having recently returned to action for the Scarlets.

Paul Sculthorpe would love to succeed Andy Farrell as Great Britain skipper. The 27-year-old said following in the footsteps of Farrell would be a challenge. He also called on the rugby league authorities to have a serious look at the number of games the top players are being asked to play.

Dent continues Adelaide progress with victory over Argentine Juan Ignacio Chela. Dent will meet Swede Joachim Johansson on Sunday after the second seed survived a tense tie-break to defeat Belgium's Olivier Rochus 6-1 7-6 (7/5) Jansson is the boyfriend of Lleyton Hewitt's sister Jaslyn.

Henman overcomes rival Rusedski at the Dubai Tennis Championships. British number one saved a match point before fighting back to win. Henman now faces Russian Igor Andreev in the last 16 of the tournament. It was the first match between the pair for three years and lasted two hours and 40 minutes.

Wales secured their first away win in the RBS Six Nations for nearly four years with a six-try victory in Rome. Jonathan Thomas, Tom Shanklin and Martyn Williams gave the visitors a 19-5 half-time advantage. Luciano Orquera did reply with one for Italy but second-half efforts from Brent Cockbain, Shane Williams and Robert Sidoli sealed victory.

Borders 19-20 Ulster. Ulster had led 20-6 with tries from Paul Steinmetz and Bryn Cunningham. A late try by Borders substitute Jonny Weston had set up a dramatic finish, but the Scottish side could not complete the fightback. The Irish province failed to add to the tally in the second half.

Safin has ruled out any chance of winning Wimbledon in the future. The 25-year-old beat Lleyton Hewitt in Sunday's Australian Open final. Safin won his first Grand Slam title at the 2000 US Open against Pete Sampras. He said he had begun to doubt whether he would win another major.

Rob Hoadley, Tom Voyce and Richard Birkett scored tries for Wasps. Mark van Gisbergen added 18 points for London Irish. Scott Staniforth ran in a consolation try for the visitors. Barry Everitt became the fourth Premiership player to reach 1,000 points.

Daniela Hantuchova faces Serena Williams in the quarter-finals of the Dubai Open. Australian Open champion Williams beat Elena Bovina 1-6 6-16-4. World number one Lindsay Davenport and Anastasia Myskina also progressed.

Carlos Moya beat Andy Roddick to give Spain a 3-1 lead in the Davis Cup. The Mallorcan became the youngest player to win the competition at 18 years and 185 days. US coach Patrick McEnroe wants his players to play more clay-court tennis.

Ana Ivanovic beat Melinda Czink 7-5 6-1 in the final of the Canberra Classic. The 17-year-old took 83 minutes to win her first WTA title. She will play 32nd seed Iveta Benesova of Czech Republic in first round of Australian Open.

Carlos Moya beats Andy Roddick to give Spain 3-1 lead in Davis Cup final. Mardy Fish beats Tommy Robredo in final dead rubber to cut Spain's winning margin. At 18 years and 187 days, Carlos Nadal is the youngest ever winner of the competition.

Safin lost the opening set to Lleyton Hewitt in the Australian Open final. But the Russian fought back brilliantly to win 1-6 6-3 6.4 6 -4. Safin says his semi-final win over world number one Roger Federer had given him confidence.

Leeds have brought in Newcastle prop Ed Kalman and Tom McGee from the Borders on loan. Fly-half Craig McMullen has joined from Narbonne. Raphael Ibanez is named at hooker for Saracens in one of four changes. Simon Raiwalui and Ben Russell are also selected in the pack.

Rusedski forced out in Marseille with a rib injury. British number two had been scheduled to play qualifier Sebastien de Chaunac. Taylor Dent caused a shock by beating second seed David Nalbandian. Third seed Joachim Johansson made it through after beating Gilles Simon.

Wales have made two changes from the team that thrashed Italy 38-8 in Rome. Coach Mike Ruddock is determined that his team will not go into their shells after their promising start to the championship. France have been criticised for the absence of traditional "French flair" as they have ground their way to victory so far this year.

Teenager Tait picked for England's Six Nations opener against Wales. The 18-year-old will play alongside Falcons' team-mate Jamie Noon. Scrum-half Matt Dawson is also recalled, despite being left out of the initial squad after a row over clashing TV and training commitments. Bath lock Danny Grewcock will also start, pending a possible citing.

Former England captain says full-backs are too far away from the action. Moore says a lack of cohesion in the forwards is one of the reasons why England have lost against Wales, France and Ireland in this year's tournament. England face Italy and Scotland in their final two Six Nations matches.

Ferrero eyes return to top form at the ABN AMRO World Tennis Tournament in Rotterdam. The 2003 French Open champion has slipped to 64 in the world after a year of illness and injuries in 2004. Ferrero opens against Rainer Schuettler and potentially faces fourth seed David Nalbandian.

Bryan twins keep US hopes alive with victory in Saturday's doubles rubber. Masters Cup champions Mike and Bob Bryan thrashed Juan Carlos Ferrero and Tommy Robredo. Victory would have given Spain the title but they were outclassed. In Sunday's reverse singles, Carlos Moya takes on Andy Roddick before Rafael Nadal faces Mardy Fish.

Andy Roddick ends 18-month association with coach Brad Gilbert. American won his first Grand Slam event at Flushing Meadows last year. He finished 2003 on top of the ATP Tour rankings, but slipped to second in 2004. Roger Federer became the first man since 1988 to win three Majors in a season.

Barkley withdrew from Bath's team for Friday's clash with Gloucester after suffering a calf injury in training. England coach Andy Robinson, who names his team on Wednesday, has called up Bath prop Duncan Bell following Phil Vickery's broken arm. Bell could make his England debut against Ireland at Lansdowne Road.

Ireland won their first Triple Crown for 29 years in 2004. They also finished runners-up in the RBS Six Nations for the second year in succession. The big one, of course, was the 19-13 defeat of World Cup champions England on their precious Twickenham turf. On the down side, Irish rugby was hit by a number of tragedies.

Lewsey puzzle over disallowed try in England's Six Nations loss to Ireland. Wasps wing insisted he grounded the ball when he was bundled over the line. Mark Cueto also puzzled as to why his try had beendisallowed by Jonathan Kaplan. England lost 24-17 in Dublin on Saturday.

Rusedski angry over supplements shortages. British number two escaped a possible ban last year. ATP struck a deal with pharmaceutical company GlaxoSmithKline to provide contamination-free drinks and nutritional bars for the men's tour. David Higdon, Vice President of the ATP, admitted: "I agree with Greg"

Italy coach John Kirwan believes his side can upset England. The two sides, both without a win, meet on 12 March at Twickenham. England have now equalled an 18-year low of four successive championship defeats, including France in Paris last season, and have lost four in a row under Andy Robinson.

Top seed Roger Federer wins 6-3, 7-6 (7-4) against David Goffin. Federers had taken the first set but Goffins fought back to take the second. The match was a repeat of last year's Wimbledon final, won by Roger in straight sets.

Kim Clijsters has denied reports that she has pulled out of January's Australian Open. The Belgian had an operation on her left wrist early in the season. Jelena Dokic, who used to compete for Australia, has opted out. Four-time champion Monica Seles is another absentee because of an injured left foot.

Ireland call up uncapped Ulster scrum-half Kieran Campbell. Roger Wilson, Ronan McCormack, Bernard Jackman and Shaun Payne also included. Gordon D'Arcy is back after injury while Munster flanker Alan Quinlan also returns to international consideration. David Wallace and Victor Costello are omitted.

Ireland win eclipses refereeing 'errors' in Six Nations clash. Referee Jonathan Kaplan was not perfect by any means and two decisions in particular made him the villain of the piece. Brian O'Driscoll's winning try was as well-conceived as they come. Charlie Hodgson's kicking display was another highlight.

Tim Henman has retired from Great Britain's Davis Cup team. Captain Jeremy Bates has touted Alex Bogdanovic and Andrew Murray as possible replacements. The 30-year-old is now set to fully focus on the ATP Tour and on winning his first Grand Slam event.

Crowds expected to line the streets of London to celebrate the opening day of the Olympic Games in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. Organisers hope the event will be a springboard for the Games to become a global sporting event. The event is being billed as the biggest ever Olympics opening ceremony in history, with more than 100,000 expected.

Ireland coach Eddie O'Sullivan heaps praise on Italy after 28-17 victory in Rome. Ireland struggled to cope with Italy's fierce start and were indebted to skipper Brian O’Driscoll, who set up tries for Geordan Murphy and Peter Stringer. "We struggled in the first half because we hadn't the football," says Ireland coach.

Former government communications chief Alastair Campbell will act as a media consultant to Sir Clive Woodward's 2005 Lions. Campbell, who left Downing Street earlier this year, will advise on media strategy before and during the tour. The Lions leave for New Zealand on 24 May, with the first Test match against the All Blacks in Christchurch on 25 June.

Martina Hingis will make her return to tennis at the Volvo Women's Open in Pattaya, Thailand, on Tuesday. The former world number one was 22 when she retired after having surgery on both ankles. She faces German Marlene Weingartner in the first round.
