Gael Monfils beats French Open champion Gaston Gaudio. The 18-year-old wild card won three of the four junior Grand Slam events last year. Fabrice Santoro, the 2000 champion, beat Sweden's Thomas Johansson. Fourth seed Mikhail Youzhny lost 6-3 7-6 (7-4) to Rafael Nadal.

Fuming Robinson blasts officials after 19-13 Six Nations loss to Ireland. Mark Cueto's first-half effort was ruled out for offside. Referee spurned TV replays when England crashed over in the dying minutes. England have lost four out of their six games since Robinson took over from Sir Clive Woodward.

Wales could follow England's lead by training with a rugby league club. England have already had a three-day session with Leeds Rhinos. Wales are thought to be interested in a similar clinic with rivals St Helens. Saints have a week's training in Portugal next week.

Taylor suffered knee ligament damage playing against Ireland in Dublin in the 2004 Six Nations championship. The 25-year-old number eight made a scoring return for Edinburgh at the weekend - his first game in a year for the capital side. Taylor has turned out for English side Saracens in recent weeks during a short-term loan to improve his fitness.

Jonah Lomu had a kidney transplant in July 2004. The 29-year-old will play his first full match for three years on 4 June. He will lead a southern hemisphere side at Twickenham. "Now it's basically bring it on!" said the giant winger.

Olympic champion Justine Henin-Hardenne will return to action in January's Sydney International tournament. The Belgian has not competed since losing her top world ranking at the US Open in September. World number three Lleyton Hewitt returns to defend his title, along with runner-up Carlos Moya.

Dallaglio has polarised opinions since his international debut in 1993. To supporters of England he could do no wrong. Rival fans see him as the epitome of the less agreeable characteristics of English rugby. The problem for England is how to replace the almost irreplaceable player. Jonny Hill, Joe Worsley and Chris Jones are all capable of stepping up.

Joachim Johansson beats Taylor Dent 7-5 6-3 to win Adelaide title. It is the Swede's second career title and his first since Memphis in 2004. Dent says he rates Johsson as a top contender at the Australian Open. The tournament starts in Melbourne on 17 January.

Dawson set for new Wasps contract. The 31-year-old scrum-half has impressed since joining from Northampton. Dawson played a vital part in England's World Cup win last year but has fallen out of favour with new coach Andy Robinson. He hopes the new deal will help him regain his England place.

Wood - Ireland can win Grand Slam this year. Ireland have finished runners-up three times, including last year, since the old Five Nations became Six in 2000. Former captain believes Wales might end their four-match losing run against England in Cardiff. Wales have not lost to Ireland since 1983.

Worcester make just one change, with Tim Collier replacing Phil Murphy in the second row. Sale are missing 14 players due to a combination of international call-ups and injuries. John Payne and Chris Rhys Jones come into the centres while scrum-half Richard Wigglesworth looks set to play on the wing.

Jimmy Connors has announced a "long-term" relationship with the Lawn Tennis Association. The American legend spent three days at the Elite Performance winter camp in La Manga. He is not the first great name to offer his services to the LTA - his long-time rival John McEnroe has done the same.

Wales came from 15-6 down to beat France 24-18 in the Six Nations. Stephen Jones kicked three penalties, a drop goal and conversion. Wales coach Mike Ruddock was elated with the win at Stade de France. He said: "After going two tries down in 12 minutes we had to show character"

Martin Johnson will retire from rugby union at the end of the season. The 34-year-old captained England to World Cup glory in 2003. His final match will be his testimonial at Twickenham on 4 June. Johnson is the only man to captain the Lions twice and the Six Nations Grand Slam.

Euan Murray has been named in the Scotland training squad after an eight-week ban. The Glasgow forward's ban for stamping ended on 2 February. Scotland face Ireland in Saturday's Six Nations match at Twickenham. Murray: "I'm just happy to be back playing and be involved with the squad"

Gareth Llewellyn will retire from Test rugby at the end of the Six Nations. The 36-year-old has won 92 caps for Wales, breaking Neil Jenkins' record. He is currently on a one-season deal with French club side Narbonne.

Tennis star Kim Clijsters will make her return from a career-threatening injury at the Antwerp WTA event in February. The 21-year-old has not played since last October after aggravating a wrist injury. Back then, a doctor treating the Belgian feared that her career may be over.

Bortolami predicts dour contest between Italy and Scotland at Murrayfield. Both sides are looking for their first win of the championship. Italy have only recorded three wins since they joined the Six Nations in 2000, but two of those have come against Scotland. Scotland played extremely well against France in Paris but not so well when Ireland came to Edinburgh.

Hodgson failed to convert three penalties and also missed a relatively easy drop goal attempt which would have given England a late win. England went in at half-time with a 17-6 lead but they failed. to score in the second half and Dimitri Yachvili slotted over four penalties.

D'Arcy injury adds to Ireland woe with captain Brian O'Driscoll also ruled out. Shane Horgan switches from wing to centre where he will be joined by Ulster's Kevin Maggs. Girvan Dempsey comes into the team to take the right wing spot.

O'Connell is rumoured to be among the front-runners for the job. The Munster lock says he is totally focused on Sunday's Six Nations clash with England. He insists Ireland will not make the mistake of being over-confident in the match in Dublin. "I have spoken to Sir Clive Woodward a few times, but not for very long, certainly nothing about summer holidays," he joked.

All Blacks captain Tama Umaga has backed New Zealand to beat the Lions. Lions boss Sir Clive Woodward is set to announce his squad for the June-July tour next month. The 31-year-old admits interest in the tour is "the biggest thing to hit NZ since Lord of the Rings" He will meet Brian O'Driscoll in Saturday's Rugby Aid match at Twickenham.

Roddick to face Saulnier in final of SAP Open in San Jose on Sunday. American top seed beat Germany's Tommy Haas 7-6 (7-3) 6-2 in semifinal. The Frenchman will move into the world's top 50 for the first time in his career.

Roger Federer beats Feliciano Lopez to reach Qatar Open semi-finals. Swiss world number one will play Nikolay Davydenko in the last four. Third seed Sebastien Grosjean was beaten by Russian third seed. Fabrice Santoro was forced to retire when 6-2 3-0 down to Albert Costa.

Serena Williams beats Lindsay Davenport to win her second Australian Open title. The 2003 champion claimed her seventh Grand Slam title, and her first since Wimbledon in 2003. Williams had looked close to quitting with a rib injury when she left the court for treatment after five games.

Wilkinson takes over from Lawrence Dallaglio, who retired from internationals in August. England's first autumn Test is against Canada on 13 November, followed by the visit of Tri-Nations champions South Africa a week later. He becomes the 117th captain of England since Fred Stokes held the position in 1871.

Bortolami predicts dour contest between Italy and Scotland at Murrayfield. Both sides are looking for their first win of the championship. Italy have only recorded three wins since they joined the Six Nations in 2000, but two of those have come against Scotland. Scotland played extremely well against France in Paris but not so well when Ireland came to Edinburgh.

Daniela Hantuchova faces Serena Williams in the quarter-finals of the Dubai Open. Australian Open champion Williams beat Elena Bovina 1-6 6-16-4. World number one Lindsay Davenport and Anastasia Myskina also progressed.

Almagro continues Spanish surge with win over Mariano Zabaleta. Rafael Nadal also reaches last eight with victory over Potito Starace. Gaston Gaudio beats Flavio Saretta in the day's late match to reach quarter-finals of Buenos Aires Open.

Mourinho takes swipe at Arsenal ahead of Newcastle clash. Chelsea beat Portsmouth 1-0 at Fratton Park on Saturday. Mourinho unhappy with amount of games in such a short space of time during this time of year. Arsenal face Newcastle on Wednesday night at St James' Park.

Carlos Moya becomes the first man to successfully defend the Chennai Open title. The Spaniard then donated his £28,000 prize money to relief efforts for the victims of the Asian tsunami. His contribution follows pledges by four other players to donate their prizeMoney from the tournament, which went ahead after the disaster.

Wales and Ireland face a potential Grand Slam play-off in three weeks' time. England are enduring their worst run in the championship since 1987. Italy continue the elusive search for their first Six Nations away win. Scotland have not won the title since 1985 and last clinched one in 1948.

England coach Andy Robinson has called on ex-international referees Colin High and Steve Lander to analyse several of Jonathan Kaplan's decisions. England were beaten 19-13 by the Irish in Dublin, their third straight defeat in the 2005 Six Nations. High, the Rugby Football Union's referees' manager, claimed Kaplan made three major errors.

Martina Hingis will play at the Volvo Women's Open in Pattaya. The former world number one will be doing charity work in the region. Her last WTA event was in Filderstadt, Germany, in October 2002, when she lost to Elena Dementieva.

Kim Clijsters has denied reports that she has pulled out of January's Australian Open because of her persistent wrist injury. Open chief Paul McNamee had said: "Kim's wrist obviously isn't going to be rehabilitated." But her spokesman insisted she had simply delayed submitting her entry. The Belgian had an operation on her left wrist early in the season.

O'Sullivan keeps his powder dry in the run-up to this season's Six Nations Championship. He decreed after the 2003 World Cup that players should have a decent conditioning period during the year. Ireland are being earmarked as hot favourites in many quarters to go the whole hog. They can live up to their success and take a further step up the ladder.

Four members of the executive board, including the chairman, David Mackay, have resigned after a simmering row. Former Scotland international Finlay Calder fears civil war at the SRU could seriously hamper his country's RBS Six Nations campaign. Calder said: "This is terrible news for every level of Scottish rugby"

Moya made up for missing Spain's 2000 victory through injury. He beat Andy Roddick to give the hosts an unassailable 3-1 lead. "I have woken up so many nights dreaming of this day," said Moya. US coach Patrick McEnroe wants the US team to play more clay tennis.

Koubek suspended after drugs test at this year's French Open. Austrian believes an injection given to him by an Austrian doctor to treat a wrist injury is to blame for producing traces of the substance in his system. The 27-year-old will miss the Australian Open and the Davis Cup in Australia.

Bath prop Duncan Bell has been added to England's 30-man squad to face Ireland in the RBS Six Nations. Bell, 30, had set his sights on an international career with Wales. But last December, the International Rugby Board confirmed that he could only be eligible for England as he had travelled on tour with them in 1998.

O'Gara revels in Ireland victory over England. Munster number 10 kicked a total of 14 points, including two drop goals. Ireland captain Brian O'Driscoll scored his side's only try in 19-13 win. England coach Andy Robinson said he was certain Mark Cueto was onside for a disallowed try.

Injury sidelines Philippoussis from Sydney International tennis tournament. Defending women's champion Justine Henin-Hardenne is also out of the Sydney event because of a knee injury. Number one men's seed Lleyton Hewitt begins his quest for a fourth Sydney title on Tuesday.

Umaga ready for "fearsome" Lions ahead of their summer tour. All Blacks captain backs New Zealand to win three-Test series against the Lions. Lions boss Sir Clive Woodward is set to announce his squad for the June-July tour next month. Umaga will meet O'Driscoll in Saturday's Rugby Aid match at Twickenham.

New Zealand's first rugby match was played in Nelson Town in 1870. The All Blacks first toured Europe in 1905, winning all 30 of their games. Their 2-3-2 scrum formation left them short of possession at times. New Zealand and South Africa have the greatest rivalry in rugby.

Hewitt beaten 7-6 (7-4) 6-3 by American Taylor Dent. Dent will face Juan Ignacio Chela next in quarter-finals. Olivier Rochus beats Nicolas Kiefer to reach last four. Second seed Joachim Johansson beats compatriot Thomas Enqvist.

Ferguson hails Man Utd's resolve in 1-0 win at Aston Villa. The Old Trafford boss also hailed senior stars Ryan Giggs and Roy Keane. "We showed lots of character and guts and we weren't going to lose," he said. 'Giggs was a tremendous threat and he brings tremendous penetration,' he added.

Robinson out of Six Nations with a torn ligament in his right thumb. The 30-year-old will undergo an operation on Friday but England have yet to name a replacement skipper. England will announce their squad for the 12 March game against Italy on Saturday. Jonny Wilkinson, Mike Tindall, Will Greenwood, Julian White and Phil Vickery are already missing.

Former world number one Jimmy Connors is planning a long-term relationship with the Lawn Tennis Association. The American spent three days at the LTA's annual Elite Performance winter camp in La Manga earlier this week. He has also agreed to commentate for the BBC at next year's Wimbledon Championships.

Two converted tries from Olly Barkley and Josh Lewsey helped the world champions to a 17-6 half-time lead. But Charlie Hodgson and Barkley missed six penalties between them, while Dimitri Yachvili landed six for France to put the visitors in front. England could have won the game with three minutes left, but Hodgman pushed an easy drop goal opportunity wide.

World Cup winners Lawrence Dallaglio, Neil Back and Martin Johnson had all been thought to be in the frame for next summer's tour to New Zealand. Woodward: "I would have to have a compulsive reason to pick any player who is not available to international rugby"

Gavin Henson scored a match-winning penalty for Wales against England. The 23-year-old also had a hand in the game's only try. His defence was a major feature of the match, his principal victim poor old, or rather young, Mathew Tait.

Prop Jones ready for hard graft against France. Wales have won two of their last three visits to the Stade de France, having secured back-to-back wins under Graham Henry in 1999 and 2001. Mike Ruddock's team is now one of international rugby's most potent attacking threats.

Conchita Martinez beats Roberta Vinci at the Qatar Open in Doha. The 1994 Wimbledon champion comes from a set down to win. Martinez will now face French Open champion Anastasia Myskina in the second round. Fifth seed Patty Schnyder needed three sets to beat China's Na Li.

Lindsay Davenport hits out at Wimbledon over equal prize money for women. World number one criticises All England Club chairman Tim Phillips. Club denies Phillips made the remark, insisting: "He definitely didn't say it" Dubai Duty Free event will join US and Australian Opens in offering equal money.

Tim Henman beats David Nalbandian 6-1 7-5 at Kooyong Classic exhibition tournament. British number one will next play Roger Federer at Australian Open warm-up event. Andre Agassi beats Nicolas Massu in his first match for over two months. Andy Roddick beats Ivan Ljubicic, who replaced Paradorn Srichaphan.

Andre Agassi pulls out of the Australian Open with a hip injury. The 34-year-old will have an MRI scan to discover the extent of his problem. He was serving at 5-6 down in the first set to fellow American Andy Roddick when he decided to quit.

Wales centre Sonny Parker and number eight Ryan Jones will miss Saturday's game with Italy because of injury. Jones damaged his collar bone after coming on as a replacement against England and joins flanker Colin Charvis (foot injury) on the sidelines. Mike Ruddock may make Gavin Henson his first-choice kicker in Rome.

Australian tennis coach Tony Roche has turned down an approach from Roger Federer to be the world number one's new full-time coach, say reports. Roche is happy to work with the Swiss star on a casual basis and is helping him prepare for next month's defence of his Australian Open crown.

England have now lost nine of their last 14 matches since the 2003 World Cup final. England scored first through Martin Corry but had "tries" from Mark Cueto and Josh Lewsey disallowed. Ireland next face France at Lansdowne Road in two weeks' time before the potential title decider against Wales.

Farrell saga to drag on - Lindsay. Wigan chairman Maurice Lindsay says he does not expect a quick solution to the on-going saga of Andy Farrell's possible switch to rugby union. Leicester and Saracens are leading the chase for the player, but Lindsay told the BBC it was not yet a done deal.

Half-Life 2 has been endlessly refined to get as close to perfection as could realistically be hoped. All the money - or indeed time - is on the screen. The player sees things through the eyes of Gordon Freeman, the bespectacled scientist who starred in the original 1998 Half- life. Underplaying the narrative in this way is gloriously effective.

Half-Life 2 is the best thing in its genre, and possibly, many will feel, of any genre. Running around on foot is great enough, but jumping into vehicles proves even more fun. Human foes are rendered just as well as alien ones. The stealth sections are as exhilarating as the open gun battles.

Half-Life 2 is out now for the PC. It is surely the best thing in its genre, and possibly, many will feel, of any genre. The bar has been raised so far out of sight that you have to sympathise with any game that tries to do anything remotely similar in the near future.
